{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1783915729029,"sessionID":"ses_0a65ac472ffeDn3G1fX5LbU2k8","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"call_RUWpuAq66npt3dXrHy2a75L7","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":"replaceAnchorSection\\(|MACHINE-OWNED|completed-dimensions|running-findings|next-focus|review-dimensions","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/scripts/reduce-state.cjs","include":"reduce-state.cjs"},"output":"Found 10 matches\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/scripts/reduce-state.cjs:\n  Line 1651: function replaceAnchorSection(content, anchorId, heading, body, options = {}) {\n\n  Line 1717:   // Default next-focus comes from latest iteration → first uncovered dimension → fallback.\n\n  Line 1730:   // blocked-stop permanently pinned next-focus. Fix: source recency from the\n\n  Line 1752:   updated = replaceAnchorSection(updated, 'review-dimensions', '3. REVIEW DIMENSIONS (remaining)', remainingDimensions, anchorOptions);\n\n  Line 1753:   updated = replaceAnchorSection(updated, 'completed-dimensions', '4. COMPLETED DIMENSIONS', completedDimensions, anchorOptions);\n\n  Line 1754:   updated = replaceAnchorSection(updated, 'running-findings', '5. RUNNING FINDINGS', runningFindings, anchorOptions);\n\n  Line 1755:   updated = replaceAnchorSection(\n\n  Line 1786:   updated = replaceAnchorSection(updated, 'next-focus', '11. NEXT FOCUS', nextFocus, anchorOptions);\n\n  Line 1961:     '<!-- ANCHOR:next-focus -->',\n\n  Line 1965:     '<!-- /ANCHOR:next-focus -->',\n","metadata":{"matches":10,"truncated":false},"title":"replaceAnchorSection\\(|MACHINE-OWNED|completed-dimensions|running-findings|next-focus|review-dimensions","time":{"start":1783915729000,"end":1783915729028}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_09805c47ca6b00a2016a5464d0ec4881919c7ef708489c8017"}},"id":"prt_f59a9d035001mQiTu683TFcAvD","sessionID":"ses_0a65ac472ffeDn3G1fX5LbU2k8","messageID":"msg_f59a97bb4001lRTmjsczmq8TbY"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1783915729041,"sessionID":"ses_0a65ac472ffeDn3G1fX5LbU2k8","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_v1456fKTljS3vpqxidIf3tY4","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-skill/assets/skill/skill_reference_template.md","offset":1,"limit":300},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-skill/assets/skill/skill_reference_template.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: Skill Reference File Templates\n3: description: Comprehensive templates for creating effective reference files for AI agent skills with workflows, decision logic, and validation checkpoints.\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"skill reference templates\"\n6:   - \"reference file structure\"\n7:   - \"explicit reasoning references\"\n8:   - \"reference creation guidelines\"\n9: importance_tier: normal\n10: contextType: general\n11: version: 1.8.0.16\n12: ---\n13: \n14: # Skill Reference File Templates - AI Agent Skills\n15: \n16: Templates for creating reference files in AI agent skills with deep-dive technical guidance.\n17: \n18: ---\n19: \n20: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n21: \n22: ### Location & Naming\n23: \n24: **Location:** `.opencode/skills/[skill-name]/references/`\n25: \n26: **Naming Convention:** snake_case with `.md` extension only\n27: \n28: | ✅ Valid Names | ❌ Invalid Names |\n29: |---------------|-----------------|\n30: | `implementation_workflows.md` | `ImplementationWorkflows.md` (PascalCase) |\n31: | `tool_catalog.md` | `tool-catalog.md` (kebab-case) |\n32: | `debugging_guide.md` | `DebuggingGuide.MD` (wrong case) |\n33: | `quick_reference.md` | `quickReference.md` (camelCase) |\n34: | `code_quality_standards.md` | `code quality standards.md` (spaces) |\n35: \n36: ### When to Create References\n37: \n38: **Create a reference file when:**\n39: - Multi-phase workflows with validation checkpoints\n40: - Decision trees with multiple branches\n41: - Pattern libraries with 5+ variations\n42: - Systematic debugging procedures\n43: - Tool integration details\n44: - Content exceeds 200 lines\n45: \n46: **Keep in SKILL.md when:**\n47: - Content under 200 lines\n48: - Simple workflows (3-5 steps)\n49: - Overview and \"When to Use\" sections\n50: - Essential rules (ALWAYS/NEVER/ESCALATE IF)\n51: \n52: ---\n53: \n54: ## 2. DOCUMENT STRUCTURE\n55: \n56: ### Document Structure: Title and Intro\n57: \n58: **CRITICAL: The intro after the H1 title must be 1-2 SHORT sentences only.**\n59: \n60: ```markdown\n61: ---\n62: title: [Title]\n63: description: [One-line description - same as intro]\n64: trigger_phrases:\n65:   - \"[distinctive phrase one]\"\n66:   - \"[distinctive phrase two]\"\n67:   - \"[distinctive phrase three]\"\n68: importance_tier: normal\n69: contextType: general\n70: version: 1.0.0.0\n71: ---\n72: \n73: # [Title]\n74: \n75: [1-2 SHORT sentences only. Brief hook/summary. NO subsections, NO headers here.]\n76: \n77: ---\n78: \n79: \\## 1. OVERVIEW\n80: [All detailed content goes here, NOT in the intro]\n81: \n82: ```\n83: \n84: Every reference file carries this full 5-field frontmatter block: the Skill Advisor harvests it as routing signal (3-8 lowercase multi-word `trigger_phrases` drawn from the doc's content; `importance_tier` defaults to `normal`, `important` only for formal contract docs; `contextType` one of `planning|research|implementation|general`). See [frontmatter_templates.md](../../../shared/assets/frontmatter_templates.md) for field rules.\n85: \n86: > **WARNING: DO NOT duplicate content between intro and Section 1.**\n87: > The intro is a hook; Section 1 provides the details.\n88: \n89: #### GOOD Intro Structure\n90: \n91: ```markdown\n92: # Git Commit Workflows\n93: \n94: Step-by-step workflows for creating clean, atomic commits with proper filtering.\n95: \n96: ---\n97: \n98: \\## 1. OVERVIEW\n99: \n100: ### Purpose\n101: Provides systematic workflows for analyzing changes, filtering artifacts, and creating well-structured commits.\n102: \n103: ### When to Use\n104: - Creating commits with multiple file changes\n105: - Filtering generated files from commits\n106: - Writing clear commit messages\n107: \n108: ### Core Principle\n109: Atomic commits with clear intent + filtered artifacts = maintainable Git history.\n110: ```\n111: \n112: #### BAD Intro Structure (duplicates content)\n113: \n114: ```markdown\n115: # Git Commit Workflows\n116: \n117: Step-by-step workflows for creating clean, atomic commits with proper filtering.\n118: \n119: ### Core Principle   ← WRONG: No headers in intro!\n120: Atomic commits with clear intent + filtered artifacts = maintainable Git history.\n121: \n122: ### When to Use      ← WRONG: This belongs in Section 1!\n123: - Creating commits with multiple file changes\n124: \n125: ---\n126: \n127: \\## 1. OVERVIEW\n128: \n129: ### Purpose\n130: Provides systematic workflows...  ← Now this duplicates the intro!\n131: \n132: ### Core Principle\n133: Atomic commits...  ← DUPLICATED from intro!\n134: ```\n135: \n136: #### Intro vs Section 1 Content Placement\n137: \n138: | Content Type          | Intro (after H1) | Section 1 OVERVIEW |\n139: | --------------------- | ---------------- | ------------------ |\n140: | 1-2 sentence summary  | ✅ YES            | ❌ NO (don't repeat) |\n141: | Core Principle        | ❌ NO             | ✅ YES              |\n142: | When to Use           | ❌ NO             | ✅ YES              |\n143: | Primary Sources       | ❌ NO             | ✅ YES (as \"Key Sources\") |\n144: | Purpose (detailed)    | ❌ NO             | ✅ YES              |\n145: | Prerequisites         | ❌ NO             | ✅ YES              |\n146: | Any H3 subsections    | ❌ NEVER          | ✅ YES              |\n147: \n148: ---\n149: \n150: ### What Are AI Agent Skill Reference Files?\n151: \n152: Reference files are detailed technical documentation in the `references/` directory that provide deep-dive guidance with **explicit reasoning** - making thought processes visible, showing decision logic, and analyzing root causes.\n153: \n154: **Core Purpose**:\n155: - **Technical depth** - Step-by-step reasoning with rationale\n156: - **Phased workflows** - Structured processes with validation checkpoints\n157: - **Pattern libraries** - Before/after examples, comparison tables\n158: - **Tool integration** - MCP tools, scripts, asset references\n159: - **Root cause analysis** - Systematic debugging and troubleshooting\n160: \n161: **Key Difference from Generic Documentation**:\n162: - AI agent skills = Actionable workflows with explicit reasoning\n163: - Generic docs = Information reference without decision logic\n164: \n165: ### Progressive Disclosure in Skills\n166: \n167: ```\n168: Level 1: Metadata (name + description)\n169:          └─ Always in context (~100 words)\n170:             ↓\n171: Level 2: SKILL.md body\n172:          └─ When skill triggers (<5k words)\n173:             ↓\n174: Level 3: Reference files (this document)\n175:          └─ Loaded as needed (500-3000 lines per file)\n176: ```\n177: \n178: **Reference files = Level 3**: Deep technical guidance loaded only when the agent needs specific workflow details.\n179: \n180: ---\n181: \n182: ## 3. WHEN TO CREATE REFERENCE FILES\n183: \n184: ### Create Reference File When\n185: \n186: **Workflow Complexity**:\n187: - Multi-phase workflows with validation checkpoints\n188: - Decision trees with multiple branches\n189: - Pattern libraries with 5+ variations\n190: - Systematic debugging procedures\n191: \n192: **Technical Depth**:\n193: - Root cause analysis required\n194: - Tool integration details (MCP, scripts)\n195: - Before/after code transformations\n196: - Common error patterns and fixes\n197: \n198: **Size Threshold**:\n199: - Content exceeds 200 lines\n200: - Multiple related workflows\n201: - Extensive troubleshooting needed\n202: \n203: ### Keep in SKILL.md When\n204: \n205: **Core Content**:\n206: - Overview and \"When to Use\"\n207: - High-level workflow (3-5 steps)\n208: - Essential rules (ALWAYS/NEVER/ESCALATE IF)\n209:   > **Note**: RULES sections in SKILL.md use ALL-CAPS H3 headers: `### ALWAYS`, `### NEVER`, `### ESCALATE IF` (or `####` at phase depth). See [skill_md_template.md](./skill_md_template.md) for the complete pattern.\n210: - Quick reference\n211: \n212: **Size**: Content under 200 lines\n213: \n214: ### Reference File Types for AI Agent Skills\n215: \n216: | Type                | Purpose                                | Example (snake_case)          | Size           |\n217: | ------------------- | -------------------------------------- | ----------------------------- | -------------- |\n218: | **Workflow**        | Multi-phase processes with checkpoints | `implementation_workflows.md` | 500-1500 lines |\n219: | **Pattern Library** | Code patterns with before/after        | `shared_patterns.md`          | 300-800 lines  |\n220: | **Standards**       | Rules and conventions                  | `code_quality_standards.md`   | 400-1000 lines |\n221: | **Debugging**       | Systematic troubleshooting             | `debugging_workflows.md`      | 600-1200 lines |\n222: | **Tool Guide**      | MCP/external tool integration          | `devtools_guide.md`           | 200-600 lines  |\n223: | **Quick Reference** | Commands, shortcuts, checklists        | `quick_reference.md`          | 200-400 lines  |\n224: \n225: **Note:** All reference file names use snake_case (underscores, lowercase).\n226: \n227: ---\n228: \n229: ## 4. AI AGENT SKILL REFERENCE CHARACTERISTICS\n230: \n231: ### Core Principle Statements\n232: \n233: **Purpose**: Distill philosophy into one-line wisdom\n234: \n235: > **PLACEMENT**: Core Principle goes in **Section 1 OVERVIEW**, NOT in the intro paragraph after the H1 title.\n236: \n237: **Format**:\n238: ```markdown\n239: \\## 1. OVERVIEW\n240: \n241: ### Core Principle\n242: \n243: [Single powerful statement that captures the workflow's essence]\n244: ```\n245: \n246: **Examples from Real Skills**:\n247: - \"Wait for the actual condition you care about, not a guess about how long it takes\"\n248: - \"ALWAYS find root cause before attempting fixes. Symptom fixes are failure\"\n249: - \"Atomic commits with clear intent + filtered artifacts = maintainable Git history\"\n250: \n251: ### Phased Workflows with Validation\n252: \n253: **Purpose**: Structured processes with mandatory checkpoints\n254: \n255: **Format**:\n256: ```markdown\n257: ### The [Number] Phases\n258: \n259: You MUST complete each phase before proceeding to the next.\n260: \n261: #### Phase 1: [Phase Name]\n262: \n263: **Purpose**: [What this phase accomplishes]\n264: \n265: **Actions**:\n266: 1. [Action 1]\n267: 2. [Action 2]\n268: \n269: **Validation**: `checkpoint_name`\n270: \n271: #### Phase 2: [Phase Name]\n272: \n273: [Similar structure]\n274: ```\n275: \n276: **Key Elements**:\n277: - **\"You MUST complete\"** - Mandatory language\n278: - **Named checkpoints** - `checkpoint_name` for validation\n279: - **Sequential phases** - Cannot skip ahead\n280: \n281: ### Before/After Code Examples\n282: \n283: **Purpose**: Show transformation from wrong to right\n284: \n285: **Format**:\n286: ```markdown\n287: ### [Pattern Name]\n288: \n289: **BEFORE**: [Problem description]\n290: \\```[language]\n291: // Bad code with issues\n292: // Showing what NOT to do\n293: \\```\n294: \n295: **AFTER**: [Solution description]\n296: \\```[language]\n297: // Good code with fixes\n298: // Showing correct approach\n299: \\```\n300: \n\n(Showing lines 1-300 of 1025. Use offset=301 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: Skill Reference File Templates\ndescription: Comprehensive templates for creating effective reference files for AI agent skills with workflows, decision logic, and validation checkpoints.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"skill reference templates\"\n  - \"reference file structure\"\n  - \"explicit reasoning references\"\n  - \"reference creation guidelines\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: general\nversion: 1.8.0.16\n---\n\n# Skill Reference File Templates - AI Agent Skills\n\nTemplates for creating reference files in AI agent skills with deep-dive technical guidance.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-skill/assets/skill/skill_reference_template.md","text":"---\ntitle: Skill Reference File Templates\ndescription: Comprehensive templates for creating effective reference files for AI agent skills with workflows, decision logic, and validation checkpoints.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"skill reference templates\"\n  - \"reference file structure\"\n  - \"explicit reasoning references\"\n  - \"reference creation guidelines\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: general\nversion: 1.8.0.16\n---\n\n# Skill Reference File Templates - AI Agent Skills\n\nTemplates for creating reference files in AI agent skills with deep-dive technical guidance.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Location & Naming\n\n**Location:** `.opencode/skills/[skill-name]/references/`\n\n**Naming Convention:** snake_case with `.md` extension only\n\n| ✅ Valid Names | ❌ Invalid Names |\n|---------------|-----------------|\n| `implementation_workflows.md` | `ImplementationWorkflows.md` (PascalCase) |\n| `tool_catalog.md` | `tool-catalog.md` (kebab-case) |\n| `debugging_guide.md` | `DebuggingGuide.MD` (wrong case) |\n| `quick_reference.md` | `quickReference.md` (camelCase) |\n| `code_quality_standards.md` | `code quality standards.md` (spaces) |\n\n### When to Create References\n\n**Create a reference file when:**\n- Multi-phase workflows with validation checkpoints\n- Decision trees with multiple branches\n- Pattern libraries with 5+ variations\n- Systematic debugging procedures\n- Tool integration details\n- Content exceeds 200 lines\n\n**Keep in SKILL.md when:**\n- Content under 200 lines\n- Simple workflows (3-5 steps)\n- Overview and \"When to Use\" sections\n- Essential rules (ALWAYS/NEVER/ESCALATE IF)\n\n---\n\n## 2. DOCUMENT STRUCTURE\n\n### Document Structure: Title and Intro\n\n**CRITICAL: The intro after the H1 title must be 1-2 SHORT sentences only.**\n\n```markdown\n---\ntitle: [Title]\ndescription: [One-line description - same as intro]\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"[distinctive phrase one]\"\n  - \"[distinctive phrase two]\"\n  - \"[distinctive phrase three]\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: general\nversion: 1.0.0.0\n---\n\n# [Title]\n\n[1-2 SHORT sentences only. Brief hook/summary. NO subsections, NO headers here.]\n\n---\n\n\\## 1. OVERVIEW\n[All detailed content goes here, NOT in the intro]\n\n```\n\nEvery reference file carries this full 5-field frontmatter block: the Skill Advisor harvests it as routing signal (3-8 lowercase multi-word `trigger_phrases` drawn from the doc's content; `importance_tier` defaults to `normal`, `important` only for formal contract docs; `contextType` one of `planning|research|implementation|general`). See [frontmatter_templates.md](../../../shared/assets/frontmatter_templates.md) for field rules.\n\n> **WARNING: DO NOT duplicate content between intro and Section 1.**\n> The intro is a hook; Section 1 provides the details.\n\n#### GOOD Intro Structure\n\n```markdown\n# Git Commit Workflows\n\nStep-by-step workflows for creating clean, atomic commits with proper filtering.\n\n---\n\n\\## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Purpose\nProvides systematic workflows for analyzing changes, filtering artifacts, and creating well-structured commits.\n\n### When to Use\n- Creating commits with multiple file changes\n- Filtering generated files from commits\n- Writing clear commit messages\n\n### Core Principle\nAtomic commits with clear intent + filtered artifacts = maintainable Git history.\n```\n\n#### BAD Intro Structure (duplicates content)\n\n```markdown\n# Git Commit Workflows\n\nStep-by-step workflows for creating clean, atomic commits with proper filtering.\n\n### Core Principle   ← WRONG: No headers in intro!\nAtomic commits with clear intent + filtered artifacts = maintainable Git history.\n\n### When to Use      ← WRONG: This belongs in Section 1!\n- Creating commits with multiple file changes\n\n---\n\n\\## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Purpose\nProvides systematic workflows...  ← Now this duplicates the intro!\n\n### Core Principle\nAtomic commits...  ← DUPLICATED from intro!\n```\n\n#### Intro vs Section 1 Content Placement\n\n| Content Type          | Intro (after H1) | Section 1 OVERVIEW |\n| --------------------- | ---------------- | ------------------ |\n| 1-2 sentence summary  | ✅ YES            | ❌ NO (don't repeat) |\n| Core Principle        | ❌ NO             | ✅ YES              |\n| When to Use           | ❌ NO             | ✅ YES              |\n| Primary Sources       | ❌ NO             | ✅ YES (as \"Key Sources\") |\n| Purpose (detailed)    | ❌ NO             | ✅ YES              |\n| Prerequisites         | ❌ NO             | ✅ YES              |\n| Any H3 subsections    | ❌ NEVER          | ✅ YES              |\n\n---\n\n### What Are AI Agent Skill Reference Files?\n\nReference files are detailed technical documentation in the `references/` directory that provide deep-dive guidance with **explicit reasoning** - making thought processes visible, showing decision logic, and analyzing root causes.\n\n**Core Purpose**:\n- **Technical depth** - Step-by-step reasoning with rationale\n- **Phased workflows** - Structured processes with validation checkpoints\n- **Pattern libraries** - Before/after examples, comparison tables\n- **Tool integration** - MCP tools, scripts, asset references\n- **Root cause analysis** - Systematic debugging and troubleshooting\n\n**Key Difference from Generic Documentation**:\n- AI agent skills = Actionable workflows with explicit reasoning\n- Generic docs = Information reference without decision logic\n\n### Progressive Disclosure in Skills\n\n```\nLevel 1: Metadata (name + description)\n         └─ Always in context (~100 words)\n            ↓\nLevel 2: SKILL.md body\n         └─ When skill triggers (<5k words)\n            ↓\nLevel 3: Reference files (this document)\n         └─ Loaded as needed (500-3000 lines per file)\n```\n\n**Reference files = Level 3**: Deep technical guidance loaded only when the agent needs specific workflow details.\n\n---\n\n## 3. WHEN TO CREATE REFERENCE FILES\n\n### Create Reference File When\n\n**Workflow Complexity**:\n- Multi-phase workflows with validation checkpoints\n- Decision trees with multiple branches\n- Pattern libraries with 5+ variations\n- Systematic debugging procedures\n\n**Technical Depth**:\n- Root cause analysis required\n- Tool integration details (MCP, scripts)\n- Before/after code transformations\n- Common error patterns and fixes\n\n**Size Threshold**:\n- Content exceeds 200 lines\n- Multiple related workflows\n- Extensive troubleshooting needed\n\n### Keep in SKILL.md When\n\n**Core Content**:\n- Overview and \"When to Use\"\n- High-level workflow (3-5 steps)\n- Essential rules (ALWAYS/NEVER/ESCALATE IF)\n  > **Note**: RULES sections in SKILL.md use ALL-CAPS H3 headers: `### ALWAYS`, `### NEVER`, `### ESCALATE IF` (or `####` at phase depth). See [skill_md_template.md](./skill_md_template.md) for the complete pattern.\n- Quick reference\n\n**Size**: Content under 200 lines\n\n### Reference File Types for AI Agent Skills\n\n| Type                | Purpose                                | Example (snake_case)          | Size           |\n| ------------------- | -------------------------------------- | ----------------------------- | -------------- |\n| **Workflow**        | Multi-phase processes with checkpoints | `implementation_workflows.md` | 500-1500 lines |\n| **Pattern Library** | Code patterns with before/after        | `shared_patterns.md`          | 300-800 lines  |\n| **Standards**       | Rules and conventions                  | `code_quality_standards.md`   | 400-1000 lines |\n| **Debugging**       | Systematic troubleshooting             | `debugging_workflows.md`      | 600-1200 lines |\n| **Tool Guide**      | MCP/external tool integration          | `devtools_guide.md`           | 200-600 lines  |\n| **Quick Reference** | Commands, shortcuts, checklists        | `quick_reference.md`          | 200-400 lines  |\n\n**Note:** All reference file names use snake_case (underscores, lowercase).\n\n---\n\n## 4. AI AGENT SKILL REFERENCE CHARACTERISTICS\n\n### Core Principle Statements\n\n**Purpose**: Distill philosophy into one-line wisdom\n\n> **PLACEMENT**: Core Principle goes in **Section 1 OVERVIEW**, NOT in the intro paragraph after the H1 title.\n\n**Format**:\n```markdown\n\\## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Core Principle\n\n[Single powerful statement that captures the workflow's essence]\n```\n\n**Examples from Real Skills**:\n- \"Wait for the actual condition you care about, not a guess about how long it takes\"\n- \"ALWAYS find root cause before attempting fixes. Symptom fixes are failure\"\n- \"Atomic commits with clear intent + filtered artifacts = maintainable Git history\"\n\n### Phased Workflows with Validation\n\n**Purpose**: Structured processes with mandatory checkpoints\n\n**Format**:\n```markdown\n### The [Number] Phases\n\nYou MUST complete each phase before proceeding to the next.\n\n#### Phase 1: [Phase Name]\n\n**Purpose**: [What this phase accomplishes]\n\n**Actions**:\n1. [Action 1]\n2. [Action 2]\n\n**Validation**: `checkpoint_name`\n\n#### Phase 2: [Phase Name]\n\n[Similar structure]\n```\n\n**Key Elements**:\n- **\"You MUST complete\"** - Mandatory language\n- **Named checkpoints** - `checkpoint_name` for validation\n- **Sequential phases** - Cannot skip ahead\n\n### Before/After Code Examples\n\n**Purpose**: Show transformation from wrong to right\n\n**Format**:\n```markdown\n### [Pattern Name]\n\n**BEFORE**: [Problem description]\n\\```[language]\n// Bad code with issues\n// Showing what NOT to do\n\\```\n\n**AFTER**: [Solution description]\n\\```[language]\n// Good code with fixes\n// Showing correct approach\n\\```\n","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":300,"totalLines":1025,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-skill/assets/skill/skill_reference_template.md","time":{"start":1783915729031,"end":1783915729040}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_09805c47ca6b00a2016a5464d0ec5881918f46bbf7c032827a"}},"id":"prt_f59a9d06a001mnzYf5J7jLpgeG","sessionID":"ses_0a65ac472ffeDn3G1fX5LbU2k8","messageID":"msg_f59a97bb4001lRTmjsczmq8TbY"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1783915729048,"sessionID":"ses_0a65ac472ffeDn3G1fX5LbU2k8","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_3r3HubdHpquM9UkmG0vs7ExL","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-skill/assets/skill/skill_asset_template.md","offset":1,"limit":300},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-skill/assets/skill/skill_asset_template.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: Skill Asset File Templates\n3: description: Templates and guidelines for creating asset files in AI agent skills.\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"skill asset templates\"\n6:   - \"asset file guidelines\"\n7:   - \"asset document structure\"\n8:   - \"standard asset structure\"\n9: importance_tier: normal\n10: contextType: general\n11: version: 1.8.0.19\n12: ---\n13: \n14: # Skill Asset File Templates - Creation Guidelines\n15: \n16: Templates and guidelines for creating asset files in AI agent skills.\n17: \n18: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n19: \n20: ### Location & Naming\n21: \n22: **Location:** `.opencode/skills/[skill-name]/assets/`\n23: \n24: **Naming Convention:** snake_case with appropriate extension\n25: \n26: | ✅ Valid Names | ❌ Invalid Names |\n27: |---------------|-----------------|\n28: | `frontmatter_templates.md` | `FrontmatterTemplates.md` (PascalCase) |\n29: | `config_examples.yaml` | `config-examples.yaml` (kebab-case) |\n30: | `validation_checklist.md` | `ValidationChecklist.MD` (wrong case) |\n31: | `emoji_reference.md` | `emojiReference.md` (camelCase) |\n32: \n33: ### When to Create Assets\n34: \n35: **Create an asset file when:**\n36: - Templates users apply repeatedly\n37: - Reference data >50 lines and self-contained\n38: - Multiple examples of same pattern exist\n39: - Lookup tables or decision matrices needed\n40: - Template variations for different scenarios\n41: \n42: **Keep in SKILL.md when:**\n43: - Content <30 lines\n44: - Tightly coupled to workflow logic\n45: - Needs to be visible immediately (not progressive disclosure)\n46: - Part of core instructions (RULES, WORKFLOW sections)\n47: \n48: ---\n49: \n50: ## 2. ASSET FILE TYPES\n51: \n52: ### Template Files\n53: **Purpose**: Provide copy-paste starting points for common tasks\n54: \n55: **Naming**: `[content-type]_templates.md`\n56: - Example: `frontmatter_templates.md`, `structure_templates.md`\n57: \n58: **Structure**:\n59: - One template per section\n60: - Include field descriptions\n61: - Show complete examples\n62: - Explain when to use each template\n63: \n64: **Use cases**:\n65: - Document templates (SKILL.md, commands, knowledge files)\n66: - Configuration templates (YAML, JSON)\n67: - Code templates (functions, classes, modules)\n68: \n69: ### Reference Files\n70: **Purpose**: Provide lookup tables, decision trees, or reference data\n71: \n72: **Naming**: `[topic]_reference.md`\n73: - Example: `emoji_reference.md`, `validation_reference.md`\n74: \n75: **Structure**:\n76: - Tables or lists for quick lookup\n77: - Decision matrices\n78: - Classification systems\n79: - Standards and conventions\n80: \n81: **Use cases**:\n82: - Emoji selection guides\n83: - File type classifications\n84: - Validation rule sets\n85: - Naming conventions\n86: \n87: ### Example Files\n88: **Purpose**: Show working examples of skill outputs\n89: \n90: **Naming**: `[topic]_examples.md`\n91: - Example: `optimization_examples.md`, `skill_examples.md`\n92: \n93: **Structure**:\n94: - Before/after comparisons\n95: - Annotated examples\n96: - Multiple variations\n97: - Anti-patterns to avoid\n98: \n99: **Use cases**:\n100: - Complete skill applications\n101: - Common patterns\n102: - Edge cases\n103: - Quality standards\n104: \n105: ### Guide Files\n106: **Purpose**: Detailed how-to guides for complex processes\n107: \n108: **Naming**: `[process]_guide.md`\n109: - Example: `packaging_guide.md`, `distribution_guide.md`\n110: \n111: **Structure**:\n112: - Step-by-step instructions\n113: - Troubleshooting sections\n114: - Best practices\n115: - Common pitfalls\n116: \n117: **Use cases**:\n118: - Multi-step processes\n119: - Advanced techniques\n120: - Workflow deep-dives\n121: - Integration guides\n122: \n123: ---\n124: \n125: ## 3. DOCUMENT STRUCTURE\n126: \n127: ### Title and Intro\n128: \n129: **CRITICAL: The intro after the H1 title must be 1-2 SHORT sentences only.**\n130: \n131: ```markdown\n132: ---\n133: title: [Title]\n134: description: [One-line description - same as intro]\n135: trigger_phrases:\n136:   - \"[distinctive phrase one]\"\n137:   - \"[distinctive phrase two]\"\n138:   - \"[distinctive phrase three]\"\n139: importance_tier: normal\n140: contextType: general\n141: version: 1.0.0.0\n142: ---\n143: \n144: # [Title]\n145: \n146: [1-2 SHORT sentences only. Brief hook/summary. NO subsections, NO headers here.]\n147: \n148: \\## 1. OVERVIEW\n149: \n150: ### Purpose\n151: \n152: [Why this asset exists]\n153: \n154: ### Usage\n155: \n156: [How to use this asset - copy instructions, customization notes]\n157: \n158: ---\n159: \n160: \\## 2. [Content Section]\n161: \n162: [The actual template/checklist/snippet content]\n163: \n164: ---\n165: \n166: ## N. Related Resources (optional, if present must be last)\n167: \n168: [Links to related files]\n169: \n170: ```\n171: \n172: Every asset file carries this full 5-field frontmatter block: the Skill Advisor harvests it as routing signal (3-8 lowercase multi-word `trigger_phrases` drawn from the doc's content; `importance_tier` defaults to `normal`; `contextType` one of `planning|research|implementation|general`). See [frontmatter_templates.md](../../../shared/assets/frontmatter_templates.md) for field rules.\n173: \n174: > **WARNING: DO NOT duplicate content between intro and OVERVIEW section.**\n175: > The intro is a hook; OVERVIEW provides the details.\n176: \n177: #### GOOD Intro Structure\n178: \n179: ```markdown\n180: # Git Commit Templates\n181: \n182: Copy-paste templates for creating well-structured commit messages.\n183: \n184: \\## 1. OVERVIEW\n185: \n186: ### Purpose\n187: \n188: Provides consistent commit message formats for atomic commits...\n189: \n190: ### Usage\n191: \n192: Copy the appropriate template based on commit type...\n193: \n194: ---\n195: \n196: \\## 2. COMMIT TEMPLATES\n197: ...\n198: ```\n199: \n200: #### BAD Intro Structure (too long, has subsections)\n201: \n202: ```markdown\n203: # Git Commit Templates\n204: \n205: Copy-paste templates for creating well-structured commit messages.\n206: \n207: ### Core Principle    ← WRONG: No headers in intro!\n208: Atomic commits with clear intent = maintainable history.\n209: \n210: ### When to Use       ← WRONG: This belongs in OVERVIEW section!\n211: - Creating new features\n212: - Fixing bugs\n213: \n214: ---\n215: ```\n216: \n217: ### Intro vs OVERVIEW Content Placement\n218: \n219: | Content Type          | Intro (after H1) | OVERVIEW Section       |\n220: | --------------------- | ---------------- | ---------------------- |\n221: | 1-2 sentence summary  | ✅ YES            | ❌ NO (don't repeat)    |\n222: | Core Principle        | ❌ NO             | ✅ YES (in Purpose)     |\n223: | When to Use           | ❌ NO             | ✅ YES (in Purpose)     |\n224: | How to copy/customize | ❌ NO             | ✅ YES (in Usage)       |\n225: | Prerequisites         | ❌ NO             | ✅ YES (in Usage)       |\n226: | Any H2/H3 subsections | ❌ NEVER          | ✅ YES                  |\n227: \n228: ---\n229: \n230: ## 4. STANDARD ASSET STRUCTURE\n231: \n232: **Template**:\n233: \n234: ```markdown\n235: ---\n236: title: Asset Title - Descriptive Subtitle\n237: description: One-line description of what this asset provides\n238: trigger_phrases:\n239:   - \"[distinctive phrase one]\"\n240:   - \"[distinctive phrase two]\"\n241:   - \"[distinctive phrase three]\"\n242: importance_tier: normal\n243: contextType: general\n244: version: 1.0.0.0\n245: ---\n246: \n247: # Asset Title - Descriptive Subtitle\n248: \n249: Brief introduction (1-2 sentences) explaining what this asset provides and when to use it.\n250: \n251: \\## 1. OVERVIEW\n252: \n253: ### Purpose\n254: \n255: [Why this asset exists, what problem it solves]\n256: \n257: ### Usage\n258: \n259: [How to use this asset - copy instructions, customization notes]\n260: \n261: ---\n262: \n263: \\## 2. SECTION NAME\n264: \n265: **Key Points**:\n266: - Point 1\n267: - Point 2\n268: - Point 3\n269: \n270: **Template**:\n271: ```[language]\n272: # Template content here\n273: # With explanatory comments\n274: ```\n275: \n276: **Field Guidelines**:\n277: \n278: **`field_name`**:\n279: - Description of field\n280: - Format requirements\n281: - Example: `value-example`\n282: \n283: **Complete Example**:\n284: ```[language]\n285: # Complete working example\n286: # Ready to copy and adapt\n287: ```\n288: \n289: ---\n290: \n291: \\## 3. SECTION NAME\n292: \n293: [Continue pattern...]\n294: \n295: ---\n296: \n297: ## N. RELATED RESOURCES\n298: \n299: [Links to related files - MUST be last section if present]\n300: \n\n(Showing lines 1-300 of 946. Use offset=301 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: Skill Asset File Templates\ndescription: Templates and guidelines for creating asset files in AI agent skills.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"skill asset templates\"\n  - \"asset file guidelines\"\n  - \"asset document structure\"\n  - \"standard asset structure\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: general\nversion: 1.8.0.19\n---\n\n# Skill Asset File Templates - Creation Guidelines\n\nTemplates and guidelines for creating asset files in AI agent skills.\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Location & Naming","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-skill/assets/skill/skill_asset_template.md","text":"---\ntitle: Skill Asset File Templates\ndescription: Templates and guidelines for creating asset files in AI agent skills.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"skill asset templates\"\n  - \"asset file guidelines\"\n  - \"asset document structure\"\n  - \"standard asset structure\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: general\nversion: 1.8.0.19\n---\n\n# Skill Asset File Templates - Creation Guidelines\n\nTemplates and guidelines for creating asset files in AI agent skills.\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Location & Naming\n\n**Location:** `.opencode/skills/[skill-name]/assets/`\n\n**Naming Convention:** snake_case with appropriate extension\n\n| ✅ Valid Names | ❌ Invalid Names |\n|---------------|-----------------|\n| `frontmatter_templates.md` | `FrontmatterTemplates.md` (PascalCase) |\n| `config_examples.yaml` | `config-examples.yaml` (kebab-case) |\n| `validation_checklist.md` | `ValidationChecklist.MD` (wrong case) |\n| `emoji_reference.md` | `emojiReference.md` (camelCase) |\n\n### When to Create Assets\n\n**Create an asset file when:**\n- Templates users apply repeatedly\n- Reference data >50 lines and self-contained\n- Multiple examples of same pattern exist\n- Lookup tables or decision matrices needed\n- Template variations for different scenarios\n\n**Keep in SKILL.md when:**\n- Content <30 lines\n- Tightly coupled to workflow logic\n- Needs to be visible immediately (not progressive disclosure)\n- Part of core instructions (RULES, WORKFLOW sections)\n\n---\n\n## 2. ASSET FILE TYPES\n\n### Template Files\n**Purpose**: Provide copy-paste starting points for common tasks\n\n**Naming**: `[content-type]_templates.md`\n- Example: `frontmatter_templates.md`, `structure_templates.md`\n\n**Structure**:\n- One template per section\n- Include field descriptions\n- Show complete examples\n- Explain when to use each template\n\n**Use cases**:\n- Document templates (SKILL.md, commands, knowledge files)\n- Configuration templates (YAML, JSON)\n- Code templates (functions, classes, modules)\n\n### Reference Files\n**Purpose**: Provide lookup tables, decision trees, or reference data\n\n**Naming**: `[topic]_reference.md`\n- Example: `emoji_reference.md`, `validation_reference.md`\n\n**Structure**:\n- Tables or lists for quick lookup\n- Decision matrices\n- Classification systems\n- Standards and conventions\n\n**Use cases**:\n- Emoji selection guides\n- File type classifications\n- Validation rule sets\n- Naming conventions\n\n### Example Files\n**Purpose**: Show working examples of skill outputs\n\n**Naming**: `[topic]_examples.md`\n- Example: `optimization_examples.md`, `skill_examples.md`\n\n**Structure**:\n- Before/after comparisons\n- Annotated examples\n- Multiple variations\n- Anti-patterns to avoid\n\n**Use cases**:\n- Complete skill applications\n- Common patterns\n- Edge cases\n- Quality standards\n\n### Guide Files\n**Purpose**: Detailed how-to guides for complex processes\n\n**Naming**: `[process]_guide.md`\n- Example: `packaging_guide.md`, `distribution_guide.md`\n\n**Structure**:\n- Step-by-step instructions\n- Troubleshooting sections\n- Best practices\n- Common pitfalls\n\n**Use cases**:\n- Multi-step processes\n- Advanced techniques\n- Workflow deep-dives\n- Integration guides\n\n---\n\n## 3. DOCUMENT STRUCTURE\n\n### Title and Intro\n\n**CRITICAL: The intro after the H1 title must be 1-2 SHORT sentences only.**\n\n```markdown\n---\ntitle: [Title]\ndescription: [One-line description - same as intro]\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"[distinctive phrase one]\"\n  - \"[distinctive phrase two]\"\n  - \"[distinctive phrase three]\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: general\nversion: 1.0.0.0\n---\n\n# [Title]\n\n[1-2 SHORT sentences only. Brief hook/summary. NO subsections, NO headers here.]\n\n\\## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Purpose\n\n[Why this asset exists]\n\n### Usage\n\n[How to use this asset - copy instructions, customization notes]\n\n---\n\n\\## 2. [Content Section]\n\n[The actual template/checklist/snippet content]\n\n---\n\n## N. Related Resources (optional, if present must be last)\n\n[Links to related files]\n\n```\n\nEvery asset file carries this full 5-field frontmatter block: the Skill Advisor harvests it as routing signal (3-8 lowercase multi-word `trigger_phrases` drawn from the doc's content; `importance_tier` defaults to `normal`; `contextType` one of `planning|research|implementation|general`). See [frontmatter_templates.md](../../../shared/assets/frontmatter_templates.md) for field rules.\n\n> **WARNING: DO NOT duplicate content between intro and OVERVIEW section.**\n> The intro is a hook; OVERVIEW provides the details.\n\n#### GOOD Intro Structure\n\n```markdown\n# Git Commit Templates\n\nCopy-paste templates for creating well-structured commit messages.\n\n\\## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Purpose\n\nProvides consistent commit message formats for atomic commits...\n\n### Usage\n\nCopy the appropriate template based on commit type...\n\n---\n\n\\## 2. COMMIT TEMPLATES\n...\n```\n\n#### BAD Intro Structure (too long, has subsections)\n\n```markdown\n# Git Commit Templates\n\nCopy-paste templates for creating well-structured commit messages.\n\n### Core Principle    ← WRONG: No headers in intro!\nAtomic commits with clear intent = maintainable history.\n\n### When to Use       ← WRONG: This belongs in OVERVIEW section!\n- Creating new features\n- Fixing bugs\n\n---\n```\n\n### Intro vs OVERVIEW Content Placement\n\n| Content Type          | Intro (after H1) | OVERVIEW Section       |\n| --------------------- | ---------------- | ---------------------- |\n| 1-2 sentence summary  | ✅ YES            | ❌ NO (don't repeat)    |\n| Core Principle        | ❌ NO             | ✅ YES (in Purpose)     |\n| When to Use           | ❌ NO             | ✅ YES (in Purpose)     |\n| How to copy/customize | ❌ NO             | ✅ YES (in Usage)       |\n| Prerequisites         | ❌ NO             | ✅ YES (in Usage)       |\n| Any H2/H3 subsections | ❌ NEVER          | ✅ YES                  |\n\n---\n\n## 4. STANDARD ASSET STRUCTURE\n\n**Template**:\n\n```markdown\n---\ntitle: Asset Title - Descriptive Subtitle\ndescription: One-line description of what this asset provides\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"[distinctive phrase one]\"\n  - \"[distinctive phrase two]\"\n  - \"[distinctive phrase three]\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: general\nversion: 1.0.0.0\n---\n\n# Asset Title - Descriptive Subtitle\n\nBrief introduction (1-2 sentences) explaining what this asset provides and when to use it.\n\n\\## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Purpose\n\n[Why this asset exists, what problem it solves]\n\n### Usage\n\n[How to use this asset - copy instructions, customization notes]\n\n---\n\n\\## 2. SECTION NAME\n\n**Key Points**:\n- Point 1\n- Point 2\n- Point 3\n\n**Template**:\n```[language]\n# Template content here\n# With explanatory comments\n```\n\n**Field Guidelines**:\n\n**`field_name`**:\n- Description of field\n- Format requirements\n- Example: `value-example`\n\n**Complete Example**:\n```[language]\n# Complete working example\n# Ready to copy and adapt\n```\n\n---\n\n\\## 3. SECTION NAME\n\n[Continue pattern...]\n\n---\n\n## N. RELATED RESOURCES\n\n[Links to related files - MUST be last section if present]\n","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":300,"totalLines":946,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-skill/assets/skill/skill_asset_template.md","time":{"start":1783915729038,"end":1783915729047}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_09805c47ca6b00a2016a5464d0ec608191a3325d7125018791"}},"id":"prt_f59a9d0890013QCnBBx8I7XfkZ","sessionID":"ses_0a65ac472ffeDn3G1fX5LbU2k8","messageID":"msg_f59a97bb4001lRTmjsczmq8TbY"}}
