{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1783915968330,"sessionID":"ses_0a65ac472ffeDn3G1fX5LbU2k8","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_ozAbGr5odsKHiMwpmCnkI3te","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-opencode/references/rust/style_guide/interop_errors_and_parity.md","offset":1,"limit":100},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-opencode/references/rust/style_guide/interop_errors_and_parity.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: Rust/TypeScript Interop — Errors, Parity & Related Resources\n3: description: Formatting standards, naming conventions, and TypeScript interoperability rules for Rust files in the OpenCode development environment. — Rust/TypeScript Interop — Errors, Parity & Related Resources.\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"rust typescript interop errors parity related resources\"\n6:   - \"rust interop errors and parity\"\n7:   - \"rust style guidance\"\n8: importance_tier: normal\n9: contextType: implementation\n10: version: 1.0.0.0\n11: ---\n12: \n13: # Rust/TypeScript Interop — Errors, Parity & Related Resources\n14: \n15: Formatting standards, naming conventions, and TypeScript interoperability rules for Rust files in the OpenCode development environment.\n16: \n17: ---\n18: \n19: ### Error Style\n20: \n21: Core public operations return domain-specific `Result` values backed by `thiserror`.\n22: \n23: ```rust\n24: use thiserror::Error;\n25: \n26: #[derive(Debug, Error)]\n27: pub enum RankingError {\n28:     #[error(\"candidate identifier must not be empty\")]\n29:     EmptyIdentifier,\n30: \n31:     #[error(\"candidate score must be finite\")]\n32:     NonFiniteScore,\n33: \n34:     #[error(\"candidate limit {limit} exceeds maximum {maximum}\")]\n35:     LimitExceeded {\n36:         limit: u32,\n37:         maximum: u32,\n38:     },\n39: }\n40: ```\n41: \n42: Rules:\n43: \n44: - Core errors contain adapter-relevant structured context.\n45: - Core errors contain no napi-rs, WASM, or Node runtime types.\n46: - `anyhow` is prohibited in pure-core public APIs and exported functions.\n47: - `anyhow` MAY be used in sidecar `main`, build tooling, and the outermost non-ABI shell.\n48: - Every adapter owns one exhaustive mapping from core errors to stable JavaScript errors.\n49: - Error messages and codes covered by TypeScript contracts are golden-tested.\n50: - Panic only for an impossible internal invariant, never for recoverable boundary input.\n51: \n52: ### Exhaustive Adapter Error Mapping\n53: \n54: ```rust\n55: #[derive(Debug)]\n56: struct JsErrorShape {\n57:     code: &'static str,\n58:     message: String,\n59: }\n60: \n61: fn map_ranking_error(error: RankingError) -> JsErrorShape {\n62:     match error {\n63:         RankingError::EmptyIdentifier => JsErrorShape {\n64:             code: \"INVALID_IDENTIFIER\",\n65:             message: error.to_string(),\n66:         },\n67:         RankingError::NonFiniteScore => JsErrorShape {\n68:             code: \"NON_FINITE_SCORE\",\n69:             message: error.to_string(),\n70:         },\n71:         RankingError::LimitExceeded { .. } => JsErrorShape {\n72:             code: \"LIMIT_EXCEEDED\",\n73:             message: error.to_string(),\n74:         },\n75:     }\n76: }\n77: ```\n78: \n79: The adapter must also preserve whether the existing TypeScript operation throws synchronously or rejects a Promise.\n80: \n81: ### Panic-Free Boundary Validation\n82: \n83: Do not use:\n84: \n85: ```rust\n86: let score = input.parse::<f64>().unwrap();\n87: let first = candidates[0].clone();\n88: let ordering = left.score.partial_cmp(&right.score).unwrap();\n89: ```\n90: \n91: Use typed failures:\n92: \n93: ```rust\n94: use std::num::ParseFloatError;\n95: \n96: fn parse_score(input: &str) -> Result<f64, ParseFloatError> {\n97:     input.parse::<f64>()\n98: }\n99: \n100: fn first_candidate(candidates: &[String]) -> Option<&str> {\n\n(Showing lines 1-100 of 321. Use offset=101 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: Rust/TypeScript Interop — Errors, Parity & Related Resources\ndescription: Formatting standards, naming conventions, and TypeScript interoperability rules for Rust files in the OpenCode development environment. — Rust/TypeScript Interop — Errors, Parity & Related Resources.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"rust typescript interop errors parity related resources\"\n  - \"rust interop errors and parity\"\n  - \"rust style guidance\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 1.0.0.0\n---\n\n# Rust/TypeScript Interop — Errors, Parity & Related Resources\n\nFormatting standards, naming conventions, and TypeScript interoperability rules for Rust files in the OpenCode development environment.\n\n---\n\n### Error Style\n","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-opencode/references/rust/style_guide/interop_errors_and_parity.md","text":"---\ntitle: Rust/TypeScript Interop — Errors, Parity & Related Resources\ndescription: Formatting standards, naming conventions, and TypeScript interoperability rules for Rust files in the OpenCode development environment. — Rust/TypeScript Interop — Errors, Parity & Related Resources.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"rust typescript interop errors parity related resources\"\n  - \"rust interop errors and parity\"\n  - \"rust style guidance\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 1.0.0.0\n---\n\n# Rust/TypeScript Interop — Errors, Parity & Related Resources\n\nFormatting standards, naming conventions, and TypeScript interoperability rules for Rust files in the OpenCode development environment.\n\n---\n\n### Error Style\n\nCore public operations return domain-specific `Result` values backed by `thiserror`.\n\n```rust\nuse thiserror::Error;\n\n#[derive(Debug, Error)]\npub enum RankingError {\n    #[error(\"candidate identifier must not be empty\")]\n    EmptyIdentifier,\n\n    #[error(\"candidate score must be finite\")]\n    NonFiniteScore,\n\n    #[error(\"candidate limit {limit} exceeds maximum {maximum}\")]\n    LimitExceeded {\n        limit: u32,\n        maximum: u32,\n    },\n}\n```\n\nRules:\n\n- Core errors contain adapter-relevant structured context.\n- Core errors contain no napi-rs, WASM, or Node runtime types.\n- `anyhow` is prohibited in pure-core public APIs and exported functions.\n- `anyhow` MAY be used in sidecar `main`, build tooling, and the outermost non-ABI shell.\n- Every adapter owns one exhaustive mapping from core errors to stable JavaScript errors.\n- Error messages and codes covered by TypeScript contracts are golden-tested.\n- Panic only for an impossible internal invariant, never for recoverable boundary input.\n\n### Exhaustive Adapter Error Mapping\n\n```rust\n#[derive(Debug)]\nstruct JsErrorShape {\n    code: &'static str,\n    message: String,\n}\n\nfn map_ranking_error(error: RankingError) -> JsErrorShape {\n    match error {\n        RankingError::EmptyIdentifier => JsErrorShape {\n            code: \"INVALID_IDENTIFIER\",\n            message: error.to_string(),\n        },\n        RankingError::NonFiniteScore => JsErrorShape {\n            code: \"NON_FINITE_SCORE\",\n            message: error.to_string(),\n        },\n        RankingError::LimitExceeded { .. } => JsErrorShape {\n            code: \"LIMIT_EXCEEDED\",\n            message: error.to_string(),\n        },\n    }\n}\n```\n\nThe adapter must also preserve whether the existing TypeScript operation throws synchronously or rejects a Promise.\n\n### Panic-Free Boundary Validation\n\nDo not use:\n\n```rust\nlet score = input.parse::<f64>().unwrap();\nlet first = candidates[0].clone();\nlet ordering = left.score.partial_cmp(&right.score).unwrap();\n```\n\nUse typed failures:\n\n```rust\nuse std::num::ParseFloatError;\n\nfn parse_score(input: &str) -> Result<f64, ParseFloatError> {\n    input.parse::<f64>()\n}\n\nfn first_candidate(candidates: &[String]) -> Option<&str> {","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":100,"totalLines":321,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-code/code-opencode/references/rust/style_guide/interop_errors_and_parity.md","time":{"start":1783915968324,"end":1783915968329}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0626a5c87cdc17c2016a5465c032ec819187c748eaa3ecb19a"}},"id":"prt_f59ad771f00152gijKRNChMwbJ","sessionID":"ses_0a65ac472ffeDn3G1fX5LbU2k8","messageID":"msg_f59ad3525001cKzYybAHwMW9vD"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1783915968397,"sessionID":"ses_0a65ac472ffeDn3G1fX5LbU2k8","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_iVa70sNUxAhc2iimTgNJZTib","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/css/patterns/tokens_state_machine_and_triggers.md","offset":1,"limit":100},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/css/patterns/tokens_state_machine_and_triggers.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: CSS Patterns - Webflow Implementation Reference\n3: description: Comprehensive CSS patterns for Webflow development including state machines, validation architecture, accessibility, and design token systems.\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"webflow css patterns\"\n6:   - \"css state machines\"\n7:   - \"design token system webflow\"\n8:   - \"css validation architecture\"\n9: importance_tier: normal\n10: contextType: implementation\n11: version: 3.5.0.4\n12: ---\n13: \n14: # CSS Patterns - Webflow Implementation Reference\n15: \n16: Comprehensive CSS patterns for Webflow development including state machines, validation architecture, accessibility, and design token systems.\n17: \n18: ---\n19: \n20: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n21: \n22: ### Purpose\n23: \n24: This reference documents CSS patterns used in example.com's Webflow implementation. These patterns solve common challenges in Webflow projects: managing hover/focus states declaratively, handling form validation visually, ensuring accessibility compliance, and maintaining consistent design tokens.\n25: \n26: ### Prerequisites\n27: \n28: Follow code quality standards for all CSS implementations:\n29: - **Naming:** Use existing conventions documented in this file\n30: - **Accessibility:** Include `prefers-reduced-motion` for all animations\n31: - See [quality_standards.md](../quality_standards/patterns_and_naming_enforcement.md) for complete requirements\n32: \n33: ### When to Use This Reference\n34: \n35: - Implementing hover/focus animations on cards or interactive elements\n36: - Building form validation with visual feedback\n37: - Ensuring keyboard vs mouse focus distinction\n38: - Working with Webflow Designer mode previews\n39: - Understanding the existing design token system\n40: \n41: ### Core Principle\n42: \n43: **Declarative CSS state management**: Use CSS custom properties as state signals (`--_state---on/off`) to drive animations, letting HTML data attributes determine behavior and CSS handle the visual response.\n44: \n45: ### Key Sources\n46: \n47: | Source File                                     | Pattern                  |\n48: | ----------------------------------------------- | ------------------------ |\n49: | `/src/1_css/animations/hover_state_machine.css` | State machine pattern    |\n50: | `/src/1_css/form/form_validation.css`           | Validation states        |\n51: | `/src/1_css/form/input_main.css`                | Keyboard focus detection |\n52: | `/src/1_css/form/input_global.css`              | Mobile/browser fixes     |\n53: \n54: ---\n55: \n56: ## 2. WEBFLOW CSS TOKEN SYSTEM\n57: \n58: ### Important Disclaimer\n59: \n60: > **WEBFLOW-SPECIFIC**: The naming convention documented in this section (`--_category---subcategory--variant`) is specific to Webflow Designer's generated CSS. This is NOT a recommended general practice for CSS custom properties. This section documents how existing code works to ensure consistency when extending it - NOT as a template for new CSS projects outside Webflow.\n61: \n62: ### Token Naming Convention\n63: \n64: Webflow Designer generates CSS custom properties with a specific naming structure:\n65: \n66: ```\n67: --_category---subcategory--variant\n68: ```\n69: \n70: **Structure breakdown:**\n71: - `--_` - Prefix (underscore after double dash)\n72: - `category` - Top-level category (e.g., `color-tokens`, `layout`, `typography`)\n73: - `---` - Triple dash separator\n74: - `subcategory` - Specific token group (e.g., `input-bg`, `border-neutral`)\n75: - `--` - Double dash separator\n76: - `variant` - State or variation (e.g., `enabled`, `hover`, `primary`)\n77: \n78: ### Color Token Categories\n79: \n80: **Input tokens** (form elements):\n81: ```css\n82: /* [SOURCE: form_validation.css:19-22, input_main.css:12-14] */\n83: \n84: /* Background states */\n85: --_color-tokens---input-bg--enabled       /* Default input background */\n86: --_color-tokens---input-bg--negative      /* Invalid/error state background */\n87: --_color-tokens---input-bg--positive      /* Valid/success state background */\n88: \n89: /* Border states */\n90: --_color-tokens---input-border--enabled   /* Default border */\n91: --_color-tokens---input-border--hover     /* Hover state border */\n92: --_color-tokens---input-border--active    /* Focused/active border */\n93: --_color-tokens---input-border--negative  /* Invalid/error state border */\n94: \n95: /* Content states */\n96: --_color-tokens---input-content--placeholder        /* Placeholder text */\n97: --_color-tokens---input-content--placeholder_hover  /* Placeholder on hover */\n98: --_color-tokens---input-content--negative           /* Error state text */\n99: ```\n100: \n\n(Showing lines 1-100 of 449. Use offset=101 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: CSS Patterns - Webflow Implementation Reference\ndescription: Comprehensive CSS patterns for Webflow development including state machines, validation architecture, accessibility, and design token systems.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"webflow css patterns\"\n  - \"css state machines\"\n  - \"design token system webflow\"\n  - \"css validation architecture\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 3.5.0.4\n---\n\n# CSS Patterns - Webflow Implementation Reference\n\nComprehensive CSS patterns for Webflow development including state machines, validation architecture, accessibility, and design token systems.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/css/patterns/tokens_state_machine_and_triggers.md","text":"---\ntitle: CSS Patterns - Webflow Implementation Reference\ndescription: Comprehensive CSS patterns for Webflow development including state machines, validation architecture, accessibility, and design token systems.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"webflow css patterns\"\n  - \"css state machines\"\n  - \"design token system webflow\"\n  - \"css validation architecture\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 3.5.0.4\n---\n\n# CSS Patterns - Webflow Implementation Reference\n\nComprehensive CSS patterns for Webflow development including state machines, validation architecture, accessibility, and design token systems.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Purpose\n\nThis reference documents CSS patterns used in example.com's Webflow implementation. These patterns solve common challenges in Webflow projects: managing hover/focus states declaratively, handling form validation visually, ensuring accessibility compliance, and maintaining consistent design tokens.\n\n### Prerequisites\n\nFollow code quality standards for all CSS implementations:\n- **Naming:** Use existing conventions documented in this file\n- **Accessibility:** Include `prefers-reduced-motion` for all animations\n- See [quality_standards.md](../quality_standards/patterns_and_naming_enforcement.md) for complete requirements\n\n### When to Use This Reference\n\n- Implementing hover/focus animations on cards or interactive elements\n- Building form validation with visual feedback\n- Ensuring keyboard vs mouse focus distinction\n- Working with Webflow Designer mode previews\n- Understanding the existing design token system\n\n### Core Principle\n\n**Declarative CSS state management**: Use CSS custom properties as state signals (`--_state---on/off`) to drive animations, letting HTML data attributes determine behavior and CSS handle the visual response.\n\n### Key Sources\n\n| Source File                                     | Pattern                  |\n| ----------------------------------------------- | ------------------------ |\n| `/src/1_css/animations/hover_state_machine.css` | State machine pattern    |\n| `/src/1_css/form/form_validation.css`           | Validation states        |\n| `/src/1_css/form/input_main.css`                | Keyboard focus detection |\n| `/src/1_css/form/input_global.css`              | Mobile/browser fixes     |\n\n---\n\n## 2. WEBFLOW CSS TOKEN SYSTEM\n\n### Important Disclaimer\n\n> **WEBFLOW-SPECIFIC**: The naming convention documented in this section (`--_category---subcategory--variant`) is specific to Webflow Designer's generated CSS. This is NOT a recommended general practice for CSS custom properties. This section documents how existing code works to ensure consistency when extending it - NOT as a template for new CSS projects outside Webflow.\n\n### Token Naming Convention\n\nWebflow Designer generates CSS custom properties with a specific naming structure:\n\n```\n--_category---subcategory--variant\n```\n\n**Structure breakdown:**\n- `--_` - Prefix (underscore after double dash)\n- `category` - Top-level category (e.g., `color-tokens`, `layout`, `typography`)\n- `---` - Triple dash separator\n- `subcategory` - Specific token group (e.g., `input-bg`, `border-neutral`)\n- `--` - Double dash separator\n- `variant` - State or variation (e.g., `enabled`, `hover`, `primary`)\n\n### Color Token Categories\n\n**Input tokens** (form elements):\n```css\n/* [SOURCE: form_validation.css:19-22, input_main.css:12-14] */\n\n/* Background states */\n--_color-tokens---input-bg--enabled       /* Default input background */\n--_color-tokens---input-bg--negative      /* Invalid/error state background */\n--_color-tokens---input-bg--positive      /* Valid/success state background */\n\n/* Border states */\n--_color-tokens---input-border--enabled   /* Default border */\n--_color-tokens---input-border--hover     /* Hover state border */\n--_color-tokens---input-border--active    /* Focused/active border */\n--_color-tokens---input-border--negative  /* Invalid/error state border */\n\n/* Content states */\n--_color-tokens---input-content--placeholder        /* Placeholder text */\n--_color-tokens---input-content--placeholder_hover  /* Placeholder on hover */\n--_color-tokens---input-content--negative           /* Error state text */\n```\n","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":100,"totalLines":449,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/css/patterns/tokens_state_machine_and_triggers.md","time":{"start":1783915968386,"end":1783915968396}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0626a5c87cdc17c2016a5465c0330c8191b1214c6b68529d1b"}},"id":"prt_f59ad776d001HGUxDUtf5mBmey","sessionID":"ses_0a65ac472ffeDn3G1fX5LbU2k8","messageID":"msg_f59ad3525001cKzYybAHwMW9vD"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1783915968439,"sessionID":"ses_0a65ac472ffeDn3G1fX5LbU2k8","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_oc3nTuuVd4Ri9JddRvknmaiv","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/implementation/observer_patterns/mutation_and_intersection.md","offset":1,"limit":100},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/implementation/observer_patterns/mutation_and_intersection.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: Observer Patterns Reference\n3: description: Browser observer APIs for reactive DOM watching, visibility detection, and scroll-triggered behaviors.\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"webflow observer patterns\"\n6:   - \"mutationobserver cms content\"\n7:   - \"intersectionobserver visibility\"\n8:   - \"resizeobserver cleanup\"\n9: importance_tier: normal\n10: contextType: implementation\n11: version: 3.5.0.4\n12: ---\n13: \n14: # Observer Patterns Reference\n15: \n16: Browser observer APIs for reactive DOM watching, visibility detection, and scroll-triggered behaviors.\n17: \n18: ---\n19: \n20: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n21: \n22: ### Purpose\n23: Production-tested patterns for MutationObserver, IntersectionObserver, and ResizeObserver in Webflow projects with proper cleanup and performance optimization.\n24: \n25: ### When to Use (Observers vs Polling)\n26: \n27: | Approach | Use When | Performance |\n28: |----------|----------|-------------|\n29: | **MutationObserver** | Watching DOM changes (attributes, children, text) | Event-driven, efficient |\n30: | **IntersectionObserver** | Detecting element visibility/scroll position | Hardware-accelerated |\n31: | **Polling (setInterval)** | External state changes not reflected in DOM | Resource-intensive, avoid |\n32: | **ResizeObserver** | Tracking element size changes | Not currently used in codebase |\n33: \n34: **Rule of thumb:** If watching the DOM, use an observer. If watching non-DOM state, consider event listeners first.\n35: \n36: ---\n37: \n38: ## 2. MUTATIONOBSERVER\n39: \n40: ### When to Use\n41: \n42: - CMS content that loads dynamically after page render\n43: - Third-party widgets that modify the DOM\n44: - Attribute changes that trigger business logic (e.g., status indicators)\n45: - Webflow interactions that change data attributes\n46: \n47: ### Basic Pattern\n48: \n49: ```javascript\n50: /**\n51:  * Basic MutationObserver setup\n52:  * @param {Element} target - Element to observe\n53:  * @param {MutationCallback} callback - Handler for mutations\n54:  * @param {MutationObserverInit} options - Observer configuration\n55:  * @returns {Function} Cleanup function\n56:  */\n57: function observe_mutations(target, callback, options = {}) {\n58:   const observer = new MutationObserver(callback);\n59:   \n60:   observer.observe(target, {\n61:     attributes: true,\n62:     attributeFilter: [],    // Empty array = watch all attributes\n63:     childList: false,\n64:     subtree: false,\n65:     characterData: false,\n66:     ...options\n67:   });\n68:   \n69:   return () => observer.disconnect();\n70: }\n71: ```\n72: \n73: ### CMS Content Observation\n74: \n75: From `nav_notifications.js` - Watching office hours indicator for status changes:\n76: \n77: ```javascript\n78: /**\n79:  * Observe a status indicator element for attribute changes\n80:  * Used when CMS or external scripts update element state\n81:  * \n82:  * @example\n83:  * // HTML: <div data-office-hours=\"indicator\" data-status=\"open\">\n84:  * observeOfficeHours();\n85:  */\n86: function observeOfficeHours() {\n87:   const indicator = document.querySelector('[data-office-hours=\"indicator\"]');\n88:   if (!indicator) {\n89:     console.log('Office hours indicator not found');\n90:     return;\n91:   }\n92: \n93:   const getStatus = () => {\n94:     const status = indicator.getAttribute('data-status');\n95:     return (status === 'open' || status === 'closed') ? status : null;\n96:   };\n97: \n98:   let currentStatus = getStatus();\n99: \n100:   const observer = new MutationObserver(() => {\n\n(Showing lines 1-100 of 379. Use offset=101 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: Observer Patterns Reference\ndescription: Browser observer APIs for reactive DOM watching, visibility detection, and scroll-triggered behaviors.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"webflow observer patterns\"\n  - \"mutationobserver cms content\"\n  - \"intersectionobserver visibility\"\n  - \"resizeobserver cleanup\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 3.5.0.4\n---\n\n# Observer Patterns Reference\n\nBrowser observer APIs for reactive DOM watching, visibility detection, and scroll-triggered behaviors.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/implementation/observer_patterns/mutation_and_intersection.md","text":"---\ntitle: Observer Patterns Reference\ndescription: Browser observer APIs for reactive DOM watching, visibility detection, and scroll-triggered behaviors.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"webflow observer patterns\"\n  - \"mutationobserver cms content\"\n  - \"intersectionobserver visibility\"\n  - \"resizeobserver cleanup\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 3.5.0.4\n---\n\n# Observer Patterns Reference\n\nBrowser observer APIs for reactive DOM watching, visibility detection, and scroll-triggered behaviors.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Purpose\nProduction-tested patterns for MutationObserver, IntersectionObserver, and ResizeObserver in Webflow projects with proper cleanup and performance optimization.\n\n### When to Use (Observers vs Polling)\n\n| Approach | Use When | Performance |\n|----------|----------|-------------|\n| **MutationObserver** | Watching DOM changes (attributes, children, text) | Event-driven, efficient |\n| **IntersectionObserver** | Detecting element visibility/scroll position | Hardware-accelerated |\n| **Polling (setInterval)** | External state changes not reflected in DOM | Resource-intensive, avoid |\n| **ResizeObserver** | Tracking element size changes | Not currently used in codebase |\n\n**Rule of thumb:** If watching the DOM, use an observer. If watching non-DOM state, consider event listeners first.\n\n---\n\n## 2. MUTATIONOBSERVER\n\n### When to Use\n\n- CMS content that loads dynamically after page render\n- Third-party widgets that modify the DOM\n- Attribute changes that trigger business logic (e.g., status indicators)\n- Webflow interactions that change data attributes\n\n### Basic Pattern\n\n```javascript\n/**\n * Basic MutationObserver setup\n * @param {Element} target - Element to observe\n * @param {MutationCallback} callback - Handler for mutations\n * @param {MutationObserverInit} options - Observer configuration\n * @returns {Function} Cleanup function\n */\nfunction observe_mutations(target, callback, options = {}) {\n  const observer = new MutationObserver(callback);\n  \n  observer.observe(target, {\n    attributes: true,\n    attributeFilter: [],    // Empty array = watch all attributes\n    childList: false,\n    subtree: false,\n    characterData: false,\n    ...options\n  });\n  \n  return () => observer.disconnect();\n}\n```\n\n### CMS Content Observation\n\nFrom `nav_notifications.js` - Watching office hours indicator for status changes:\n\n```javascript\n/**\n * Observe a status indicator element for attribute changes\n * Used when CMS or external scripts update element state\n * \n * @example\n * // HTML: <div data-office-hours=\"indicator\" data-status=\"open\">\n * observeOfficeHours();\n */\nfunction observeOfficeHours() {\n  const indicator = document.querySelector('[data-office-hours=\"indicator\"]');\n  if (!indicator) {\n    console.log('Office hours indicator not found');\n    return;\n  }\n\n  const getStatus = () => {\n    const status = indicator.getAttribute('data-status');\n    return (status === 'open' || status === 'closed') ? status : null;\n  };\n\n  let currentStatus = getStatus();\n\n  const observer = new MutationObserver(() => {","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":100,"totalLines":379,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/implementation/observer_patterns/mutation_and_intersection.md","time":{"start":1783915968435,"end":1783915968438}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0626a5c87cdc17c2016a5465c033148191862884ff07860b2c"}},"id":"prt_f59ad7784001iX6HHHiSQp3tRQ","sessionID":"ses_0a65ac472ffeDn3G1fX5LbU2k8","messageID":"msg_f59ad3525001cKzYybAHwMW9vD"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1783915968597,"sessionID":"ses_0a65ac472ffeDn3G1fX5LbU2k8","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_6JHDAw4kXPHnye7gitVaOf4Y","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/css/quality_standards/focus_has_print_and_quick_reference.md","offset":1,"limit":200},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/css/quality_standards/focus_has_print_and_quick_reference.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: Focus-Visible, :has(), Print & Quick Reference\n3: description: \"CSS quality patterns for Webflow: will-change management (set in JS, cleanup after), GPU-accelerated properties (transform/opacity only), Motion.dev-aligned easing, fluid typography. Includes CSS enforcement: custom property naming (--font-/--vw-/--component-/--state-/--global-), attribute selector case-insensitivity (i flag), BEM naming, animation property restrictions.\" — Focus-Visible, :has(), Print & Quick Reference.\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"focus visible discipline\"\n6:   - \"css has parent selector\"\n7:   - \"webflow print stylesheet\"\n8:   - \"css deployment checklist\"\n9: importance_tier: normal\n10: contextType: implementation\n11: version: 3.5.0.2\n12: ---\n13: \n14: # Focus-Visible, :has(), Print & Quick Reference\n15: \n16: Quality and enforcement guidance for focus visibility, parent-state selectors, print stylesheets, and final CSS checks.\n17: \n18: ---\n19: \n20: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n21: \n22: ### Purpose\n23: \n24: Document modern focus indicators, `:has()` parent-state patterns, print behavior, and a compact deployment checklist.\n25: \n26: ### When to Use\n27: \n28: - Migrating focus styling from `:focus` to `:focus-visible`.\n29: - Replacing parent-state class toggles with `:has()` where appropriate.\n30: - Adding print support or performing final CSS quality checks.\n31: \n32: ---\n33: \n34: ## 2. :FOCUS-VISIBLE VS :FOCUS DISCIPLINE\n35: \n36: The `:focus` pseudo-class fires for ALL focus events — keyboard tab, mouse click, programmatic focus. The `:focus-visible` pseudo-class fires ONLY when the browser determines the user needs visible focus indication (typically keyboard tab, NOT mouse click). Use `:focus-visible` for outline rings to avoid showing them on every mouse click.\n37: \n38: ### Compliant pattern\n39: \n40: ```css\n41: /* Keyboard users see the focus ring */\n42: .input:focus-visible {\n43:   outline: 4px solid var(--_color-tokens---state--focused);\n44:   outline-offset: 0;\n45: }\n46: \n47: /* Mouse-click focus does NOT show outline (no :focus rule needed) */\n48: .input {\n49:   /* Default — no outline rule */\n50: }\n51: \n52: /* Buttons: same pattern */\n53: .btn:focus-visible {\n54:   outline: 2px solid var(--_color-tokens---state--focused);\n55:   outline-offset: 2px;\n56: }\n57: ```\n58: \n59: ### Why not the body.using-keyboard pattern?\n60: \n61: The legacy pattern (in `references/webflow/css/quick_reference.md` §5) uses JS to add `body.using-keyboard` on Tab keypress, then CSS targets `body.using-keyboard :focus`. That pattern predates `:focus-visible` and is now legacy. Reasons to migrate:\n62: \n63: - `:focus-visible` is browser-native heuristic; matches user expectations across all browsers (including future ones)\n64: - Reduces JS surface area (no Tab/mousedown listeners needed)\n65: - Honors browser settings (a user with keyboard-navigation accessibility settings always sees the ring; mouse-only users never do)\n66: \n67: ### Migration path\n68: \n69: ```css\n70: /* OLD (legacy) — kept for compatibility while migrating */\n71: body.using-keyboard .input:focus {\n72:   outline: 4px solid var(--_color-tokens---state--focused);\n73: }\n74: \n75: /* NEW — modern :focus-visible */\n76: .input:focus-visible {\n77:   outline: 4px solid var(--_color-tokens---state--focused);\n78:   outline-offset: 0;\n79: }\n80: ```\n81: \n82: Both rules can coexist during migration. After all consumers update, remove the JS that toggles `.using-keyboard` and the legacy CSS.\n83: \n84: ### Browser support\n85: \n86: `:focus-visible` is supported in Chrome 86+, Firefox 85+, Safari 15.4+. For older browsers, fall back to `:focus` with the legacy `.using-keyboard` pattern OR accept that mouse users see focus rings.\n87: \n88: ### Validation prompt\n89: \n90: > **Check:** Are focus styles applied via `:focus-visible` (modern) rather than `:focus` (legacy)? Is the legacy `body.using-keyboard` pattern marked for migration?\n91: \n92: ---\n93: \n94: ## 3. :HAS() PARENT-STATE PATTERNS\n95: \n96: `:has()` (Chrome 105+, Firefox 121+, Safari 15.4+) is the long-awaited \"parent selector\" — a CSS rule can target an element based on its descendants' state. Eliminates many JavaScript-driven class toggles.\n97: \n98: ### Form-field validation parent style (without JS)\n99: \n100: ```css\n101: /* OLD pattern: JS adds .validation-invalid to [data-form-field] when input is :invalid */\n102: [data-form-field].validation-invalid {\n103:   border-color: red;\n104: }\n105: \n106: /* NEW pattern: CSS handles it via :has() */\n107: [data-form-field]:has(input:invalid) {\n108:   border-color: var(--_color-tokens---input-border--negative);\n109: }\n110: \n111: [data-form-field]:has(input:valid:not(:placeholder-shown)) {\n112:   border-color: var(--_color-tokens---input-border--positive);\n113: }\n114: ```\n115: \n116: The JS class-toggle pattern still has its place (when validation timing must be deferred until blur or submission), but for immediate parent-state styling, `:has()` is simpler and faster.\n117: \n118: ### Card with image vs no-image styling\n119: \n120: ```css\n121: /* Card layout adapts based on whether it contains an image */\n122: .card:has(.card--image) {\n123:   display: grid;\n124:   grid-template-columns: 1fr 2fr;\n125: }\n126: \n127: .card:not(:has(.card--image)) {\n128:   display: block;\n129: }\n130: ```\n131: \n132: ### Section visibility based on content presence\n133: \n134: ```css\n135: /* Hide section header if section has no content */\n136: .section:not(:has(.section--body)) {\n137:   display: none;\n138: }\n139: \n140: /* Show \"load more\" button only if there's hidden content */\n141: .list:has(.list--item.is-hidden) ~ .list--load-more {\n142:   display: block;\n143: }\n144: .list--load-more {\n145:   display: none;\n146: }\n147: ```\n148: \n149: ### Validation prompt\n150: \n151: > **Check:** Are JS-driven class-toggle patterns that target parent-state styling candidates for `:has()` migration? Is `:has()` used where it simplifies the JS↔CSS contract?\n152: \n153: ---\n154: \n155: ## 4. PRINT STYLESHEET PATTERNS\n156: \n157: Webflow doesn't generate print stylesheets. If users print pages (common for invoices, contracts, technical specs), add `@media print` rules in the Custom CSS panel.\n158: \n159: ### Standard print reset\n160: \n161: ```css\n162: @media print {\n163:   /* Hide non-printable UI */\n164:   .nav,\n165:   .footer,\n166:   .modal,\n167:   .cookie-banner,\n168:   [data-print=\"hide\"] {\n169:     display: none !important;\n170:   }\n171: \n172:   /* Force white background, black text — saves toner */\n173:   body {\n174:     background: white;\n175:     color: black;\n176:   }\n177: \n178:   /* Honor page-break hints */\n179:   h1, h2, h3 {\n180:     break-after: avoid;\n181:   }\n182: \n183:   .card,\n184:   .section {\n185:     break-inside: avoid;\n186:   }\n187: \n188:   /* Show full URLs after links (keeps printed output useful) */\n189:   a[href]::after {\n190:     content: \" (\" attr(href) \")\";\n191:     font-size: 0.85em;\n192:     color: #666;\n193:   }\n194: \n195:   /* Don't print tracking-pixel images */\n196:   img[src*=\"analytics\"],\n197:   img[src*=\"pixel\"] {\n198:     display: none;\n199:   }\n200: }\n\n(Showing lines 1-200 of 243. Use offset=201 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: Focus-Visible, :has(), Print & Quick Reference\ndescription: \"CSS quality patterns for Webflow: will-change management (set in JS, cleanup after), GPU-accelerated properties (transform/opacity only), Motion.dev-aligned easing, fluid typography. Includes CSS enforcement: custom property naming (--font-/--vw-/--component-/--state-/--global-), attribute selector case-insensitivity (i flag), BEM naming, animation property restrictions.\" — Focus-Visible, :has(), Print & Quick Reference.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"focus visible discipline\"\n  - \"css has parent selector\"\n  - \"webflow print stylesheet\"\n  - \"css deployment checklist\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 3.5.0.2\n---\n\n# Focus-Visible, :has(), Print & Quick Reference\n\nQuality and enforcement guidance for focus visibility, parent-state selectors, print stylesheets, and final CSS checks.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/css/quality_standards/focus_has_print_and_quick_reference.md","text":"---\ntitle: Focus-Visible, :has(), Print & Quick Reference\ndescription: \"CSS quality patterns for Webflow: will-change management (set in JS, cleanup after), GPU-accelerated properties (transform/opacity only), Motion.dev-aligned easing, fluid typography. Includes CSS enforcement: custom property naming (--font-/--vw-/--component-/--state-/--global-), attribute selector case-insensitivity (i flag), BEM naming, animation property restrictions.\" — Focus-Visible, :has(), Print & Quick Reference.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"focus visible discipline\"\n  - \"css has parent selector\"\n  - \"webflow print stylesheet\"\n  - \"css deployment checklist\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 3.5.0.2\n---\n\n# Focus-Visible, :has(), Print & Quick Reference\n\nQuality and enforcement guidance for focus visibility, parent-state selectors, print stylesheets, and final CSS checks.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Purpose\n\nDocument modern focus indicators, `:has()` parent-state patterns, print behavior, and a compact deployment checklist.\n\n### When to Use\n\n- Migrating focus styling from `:focus` to `:focus-visible`.\n- Replacing parent-state class toggles with `:has()` where appropriate.\n- Adding print support or performing final CSS quality checks.\n\n---\n\n## 2. :FOCUS-VISIBLE VS :FOCUS DISCIPLINE\n\nThe `:focus` pseudo-class fires for ALL focus events — keyboard tab, mouse click, programmatic focus. The `:focus-visible` pseudo-class fires ONLY when the browser determines the user needs visible focus indication (typically keyboard tab, NOT mouse click). Use `:focus-visible` for outline rings to avoid showing them on every mouse click.\n\n### Compliant pattern\n\n```css\n/* Keyboard users see the focus ring */\n.input:focus-visible {\n  outline: 4px solid var(--_color-tokens---state--focused);\n  outline-offset: 0;\n}\n\n/* Mouse-click focus does NOT show outline (no :focus rule needed) */\n.input {\n  /* Default — no outline rule */\n}\n\n/* Buttons: same pattern */\n.btn:focus-visible {\n  outline: 2px solid var(--_color-tokens---state--focused);\n  outline-offset: 2px;\n}\n```\n\n### Why not the body.using-keyboard pattern?\n\nThe legacy pattern (in `references/webflow/css/quick_reference.md` §5) uses JS to add `body.using-keyboard` on Tab keypress, then CSS targets `body.using-keyboard :focus`. That pattern predates `:focus-visible` and is now legacy. Reasons to migrate:\n\n- `:focus-visible` is browser-native heuristic; matches user expectations across all browsers (including future ones)\n- Reduces JS surface area (no Tab/mousedown listeners needed)\n- Honors browser settings (a user with keyboard-navigation accessibility settings always sees the ring; mouse-only users never do)\n\n### Migration path\n\n```css\n/* OLD (legacy) — kept for compatibility while migrating */\nbody.using-keyboard .input:focus {\n  outline: 4px solid var(--_color-tokens---state--focused);\n}\n\n/* NEW — modern :focus-visible */\n.input:focus-visible {\n  outline: 4px solid var(--_color-tokens---state--focused);\n  outline-offset: 0;\n}\n```\n\nBoth rules can coexist during migration. After all consumers update, remove the JS that toggles `.using-keyboard` and the legacy CSS.\n\n### Browser support\n\n`:focus-visible` is supported in Chrome 86+, Firefox 85+, Safari 15.4+. For older browsers, fall back to `:focus` with the legacy `.using-keyboard` pattern OR accept that mouse users see focus rings.\n\n### Validation prompt\n\n> **Check:** Are focus styles applied via `:focus-visible` (modern) rather than `:focus` (legacy)? Is the legacy `body.using-keyboard` pattern marked for migration?\n\n---\n\n## 3. :HAS() PARENT-STATE PATTERNS\n\n`:has()` (Chrome 105+, Firefox 121+, Safari 15.4+) is the long-awaited \"parent selector\" — a CSS rule can target an element based on its descendants' state. Eliminates many JavaScript-driven class toggles.\n\n### Form-field validation parent style (without JS)\n\n```css\n/* OLD pattern: JS adds .validation-invalid to [data-form-field] when input is :invalid */\n[data-form-field].validation-invalid {\n  border-color: red;\n}\n\n/* NEW pattern: CSS handles it via :has() */\n[data-form-field]:has(input:invalid) {\n  border-color: var(--_color-tokens---input-border--negative);\n}\n\n[data-form-field]:has(input:valid:not(:placeholder-shown)) {\n  border-color: var(--_color-tokens---input-border--positive);\n}\n```\n\nThe JS class-toggle pattern still has its place (when validation timing must be deferred until blur or submission), but for immediate parent-state styling, `:has()` is simpler and faster.\n\n### Card with image vs no-image styling\n\n```css\n/* Card layout adapts based on whether it contains an image */\n.card:has(.card--image) {\n  display: grid;\n  grid-template-columns: 1fr 2fr;\n}\n\n.card:not(:has(.card--image)) {\n  display: block;\n}\n```\n\n### Section visibility based on content presence\n\n```css\n/* Hide section header if section has no content */\n.section:not(:has(.section--body)) {\n  display: none;\n}\n\n/* Show \"load more\" button only if there's hidden content */\n.list:has(.list--item.is-hidden) ~ .list--load-more {\n  display: block;\n}\n.list--load-more {\n  display: none;\n}\n```\n\n### Validation prompt\n\n> **Check:** Are JS-driven class-toggle patterns that target parent-state styling candidates for `:has()` migration? Is `:has()` used where it simplifies the JS↔CSS contract?\n\n---\n\n## 4. PRINT STYLESHEET PATTERNS\n\nWebflow doesn't generate print stylesheets. If users print pages (common for invoices, contracts, technical specs), add `@media print` rules in the Custom CSS panel.\n\n### Standard print reset\n\n```css\n@media print {\n  /* Hide non-printable UI */\n  .nav,\n  .footer,\n  .modal,\n  .cookie-banner,\n  [data-print=\"hide\"] {\n    display: none !important;\n  }\n\n  /* Force white background, black text — saves toner */\n  body {\n    background: white;\n    color: black;\n  }\n\n  /* Honor page-break hints */\n  h1, h2, h3 {\n    break-after: avoid;\n  }\n\n  .card,\n  .section {\n    break-inside: avoid;\n  }\n\n  /* Show full URLs after links (keeps printed output useful) */\n  a[href]::after {\n    content: \" (\" attr(href) \")\";\n    font-size: 0.85em;\n    color: #666;\n  }\n\n  /* Don't print tracking-pixel images */\n  img[src*=\"analytics\"],\n  img[src*=\"pixel\"] {\n    display: none;\n  }\n}","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":200,"totalLines":243,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/css/quality_standards/focus_has_print_and_quick_reference.md","time":{"start":1783915968580,"end":1783915968584}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0626a5c87cdc17c2016a5465c0331c8191b10205a2626b7e1f"}},"id":"prt_f59ad7832001lTYREaeIIHMUzg","sessionID":"ses_0a65ac472ffeDn3G1fX5LbU2k8","messageID":"msg_f59ad3525001cKzYybAHwMW9vD"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1783915968609,"sessionID":"ses_0a65ac472ffeDn3G1fX5LbU2k8","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_vxpolNBikBFiXIbvya8VsI6f","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/css/quick_reference.md","offset":1,"limit":200},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/css/quick_reference.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: \"Webflow CSS Quick Reference\"\n3: description: \"CSS patterns reference for Webflow: read-only Webflow Designer token names, form validation classes (.validation-invalid/.validation-valid), prefers-reduced-motion (MANDATORY), keyboard vs mouse focus detection (.using-keyboard), CSS decision matrix.\"\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"webflow css quick reference\"\n6:   - \"webflow designer tokens\"\n7:   - \"form validation classes\"\n8:   - \"prefers reduced motion\"\n9:   - \"keyboard focus detection\"\n10:   - \"css decision matrix\"\n11: importance_tier: normal\n12: contextType: implementation\n13: version: 3.5.0.2\n14: ---\n15: \n16: # Webflow CSS Quick Reference\n17: \n18: > See [`./style_guide.md`](./style_guide.md) for CSS conventions and [`quality_standards/patterns_and_naming_enforcement.md`](quality_standards/patterns_and_naming_enforcement.md) for CSS quality patterns + enforcement. See [`../shared/dev_workflow/overview_nav_and_logging.md`](../shared/dev_workflow/overview_nav_and_logging.md) for cross-language commands and decision matrix.\n19: \n20: ---\n21: \n22: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n23: \n24: ### Purpose\n25: \n26: CSS patterns reference for the Webflow stack: read-only Webflow Designer tokens, form validation classes, prefers-reduced-motion override, keyboard-vs-mouse focus detection, decision matrix.\n27: \n28: ### When to Use\n29: \n30: - Need to read a Webflow-Designer-generated custom property\n31: - Setting form validation or focus-visible state\n32: - Looking up the decision matrix for a CSS scenario\n33: \n34: ### Core Principle\n35: \n36: Honor Webflow Designer's generated tokens; never invent parallel naming schemes.\n37: \n38: ---\n39: \n40: ## 2. PRE-COMMIT CSS CHECKLIST\n41: \n42: - [ ] Attribute selectors use `i` flag for case-insensitivity\n43: - [ ] Custom properties use semantic prefixes (`--font-*`, `--vw-*`, etc.)\n44: - [ ] GPU-accelerated properties only for animations (transform, opacity)\n45: - [ ] BEM naming: `.block--element`, `.block-modifier`\n46: \n47: ---\n48: \n49: ## 3. WEBFLOW TOKEN NAMING (READ-ONLY REFERENCE)\n50: \n51: > **IMPORTANT:** These tokens are auto-generated by Webflow's design system. This section documents the pattern for understanding existing code - do NOT create new custom properties using this convention.\n52: \n53: **Token Pattern:**\n54: ```\n55: --_category---subcategory--variant\n56: ```\n57: \n58: | Part        | Delimiter | Example           |\n59: | ----------- | --------- | ----------------- |\n60: | Category    | `--_`     | `--_color-tokens` |\n61: | Subcategory | `---`     | `---input-border` |\n62: | Variant     | `--`      | `--negative`      |\n63: \n64: **Common Tokens:**\n65: ```css\n66: /* Input backgrounds */\n67: var(--_color-tokens---input-bg--enabled)\n68: var(--_color-tokens---input-bg--negative)\n69: \n70: /* Input borders */\n71: var(--_color-tokens---input-border--enabled)\n72: var(--_color-tokens---input-border--negative)\n73: \n74: /* State colors */\n75: var(--_color-tokens---state--focused)\n76: var(--_color-tokens---state--warning)\n77: var(--_color-tokens---state--success)\n78: ```\n79: \n80: ---\n81: \n82: ## 4. FORM VALIDATION CLASSES\n83: \n84: | Class                 | Purpose             | Applied To          |\n85: | --------------------- | ------------------- | ------------------- |\n86: | `.validation-invalid` | Invalid/error state | `[data-form-field]` |\n87: | `.validation-valid`   | Valid/success state | `[data-form-field]` |\n88: \n89: ```css\n90: /* Invalid state */\n91: [data-form-field].validation-invalid input.input[data-form-input] {\n92:   border-color: var(--_color-tokens---input-border--negative);\n93:   background-color: var(--_color-tokens---input-bg--negative);\n94: }\n95: \n96: /* Valid state */\n97: [data-form-field].validation-valid #input-success {\n98:   display: flex;\n99:   opacity: 1;\n100: }\n101: ```\n102: \n103: ```javascript\n104: // Toggle validation states\n105: field.classList.remove('validation-invalid');\n106: field.classList.add('validation-valid');\n107: ```\n108: \n109: ---\n110: \n111: ## 5. REDUCED MOTION (MANDATORY)\n112: \n113: All animations MUST respect `prefers-reduced-motion`:\n114: \n115: ```css\n116: /* Default animation */\n117: .element {\n118:   transition: transform 0.3s ease-out;\n119: }\n120: \n121: /* Disable for reduced motion preference */\n122: @media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce) {\n123:   .element {\n124:     transition: none;\n125:   }\n126: }\n127: ```\n128: \n129: ```javascript\n130: // Check preference in JS\n131: const PREFERS_REDUCED_MOTION = window.matchMedia(\n132:   '(prefers-reduced-motion: reduce)'\n133: ).matches;\n134: \n135: if (!PREFERS_REDUCED_MOTION) {\n136:   animate(element, { opacity: [0, 1], y: [20, 0] });\n137: }\n138: ```\n139: \n140: ---\n141: \n142: ## 6. FOCUS DETECTION (KEYBOARD VS MOUSE)\n143: \n144: | Class             | When Applied     | Purpose            |\n145: | ----------------- | ---------------- | ------------------ |\n146: | `.using-keyboard` | User presses Tab | Show focus outline |\n147: | (no class)        | User clicks      | Hide focus outline |\n148: \n149: ```css\n150: /* Show focus outline for keyboard users */\n151: body.using-keyboard .input:focus {\n152:   outline: 4px solid var(--_color-tokens---state--focused);\n153:   outline-offset: 0;\n154: }\n155: \n156: /* Hide focus outline for mouse users */\n157: body:not(.using-keyboard) .input:focus {\n158:   outline: none;\n159: }\n160: ```\n161: \n162: ```javascript\n163: // Detection (from input_focus_handler.js)\n164: document.addEventListener('keydown', (e) => {\n165:   if (e.key === 'Tab') {\n166:     document.body.classList.add('using-keyboard');\n167:   }\n168: });\n169: \n170: document.addEventListener('mousedown', () => {\n171:   document.body.classList.remove('using-keyboard');\n172: });\n173: ```\n174: \n175: ---\n176: \n177: ## 7. CSS QUICK DECISION MATRIX\n178: \n179: | Scenario               | Pattern                              |\n180: | ---------------------- | ------------------------------------ |\n181: | Read Webflow token     | `var(--_category---sub--variant)`    |\n182: | Set validation error   | `.validation-invalid` on field       |\n183: | Set validation success | `.validation-valid` on field         |\n184: | Add animation          | Check `prefers-reduced-motion` first |\n185: | Style keyboard focus   | `body.using-keyboard :focus`         |\n186: | Hide mouse focus       | `body:not(.using-keyboard) :focus`   |\n187: \n188: ## RELATED RESOURCES\n189: \n190: - [`./style_guide.md`](./style_guide.md) — CSS naming, custom property prefixes, attribute selectors, animation CSS, file organization\n191: - [`quality_standards/patterns_and_naming_enforcement.md`](quality_standards/patterns_and_naming_enforcement.md) — will-change, GPU props, easing, fluid typography, all 4 CSS enforcement subsections\n192: - [`../javascript/quick_reference.md`](../javascript/quick_reference.md) — JS snippets and one-liners\n193: - [`../shared/dev_workflow/overview_nav_and_logging.md`](../shared/dev_workflow/overview_nav_and_logging.md) — cross-language commands, decision matrix, debugging checklist\n\n(End of file - total 193 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: \"Webflow CSS Quick Reference\"\ndescription: \"CSS patterns reference for Webflow: read-only Webflow Designer token names, form validation classes (.validation-invalid/.validation-valid), prefers-reduced-motion (MANDATORY), keyboard vs mouse focus detection (.using-keyboard), CSS decision matrix.\"\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"webflow css quick reference\"\n  - \"webflow designer tokens\"\n  - \"form validation classes\"\n  - \"prefers reduced motion\"\n  - \"keyboard focus detection\"\n  - \"css decision matrix\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 3.5.0.2\n---\n\n# Webflow CSS Quick Reference\n\n> See [`./style_guide.md`](./style_guide.md) for CSS conventions and [`quality_standards/patterns_and_naming_enforcement.md`](quality_standards/patterns_and_naming_enforcement.md) for CSS quality patterns + enforcement. See [`../shared/dev_workflow/overview_nav_and_logging.md`](../shared/dev_workflow/overview_nav_and_logging.md) for cross-language commands and decision matrix.\n\n---","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/css/quick_reference.md","text":"---\ntitle: \"Webflow CSS Quick Reference\"\ndescription: \"CSS patterns reference for Webflow: read-only Webflow Designer token names, form validation classes (.validation-invalid/.validation-valid), prefers-reduced-motion (MANDATORY), keyboard vs mouse focus detection (.using-keyboard), CSS decision matrix.\"\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"webflow css quick reference\"\n  - \"webflow designer tokens\"\n  - \"form validation classes\"\n  - \"prefers reduced motion\"\n  - \"keyboard focus detection\"\n  - \"css decision matrix\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 3.5.0.2\n---\n\n# Webflow CSS Quick Reference\n\n> See [`./style_guide.md`](./style_guide.md) for CSS conventions and [`quality_standards/patterns_and_naming_enforcement.md`](quality_standards/patterns_and_naming_enforcement.md) for CSS quality patterns + enforcement. See [`../shared/dev_workflow/overview_nav_and_logging.md`](../shared/dev_workflow/overview_nav_and_logging.md) for cross-language commands and decision matrix.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Purpose\n\nCSS patterns reference for the Webflow stack: read-only Webflow Designer tokens, form validation classes, prefers-reduced-motion override, keyboard-vs-mouse focus detection, decision matrix.\n\n### When to Use\n\n- Need to read a Webflow-Designer-generated custom property\n- Setting form validation or focus-visible state\n- Looking up the decision matrix for a CSS scenario\n\n### Core Principle\n\nHonor Webflow Designer's generated tokens; never invent parallel naming schemes.\n\n---\n\n## 2. PRE-COMMIT CSS CHECKLIST\n\n- [ ] Attribute selectors use `i` flag for case-insensitivity\n- [ ] Custom properties use semantic prefixes (`--font-*`, `--vw-*`, etc.)\n- [ ] GPU-accelerated properties only for animations (transform, opacity)\n- [ ] BEM naming: `.block--element`, `.block-modifier`\n\n---\n\n## 3. WEBFLOW TOKEN NAMING (READ-ONLY REFERENCE)\n\n> **IMPORTANT:** These tokens are auto-generated by Webflow's design system. This section documents the pattern for understanding existing code - do NOT create new custom properties using this convention.\n\n**Token Pattern:**\n```\n--_category---subcategory--variant\n```\n\n| Part        | Delimiter | Example           |\n| ----------- | --------- | ----------------- |\n| Category    | `--_`     | `--_color-tokens` |\n| Subcategory | `---`     | `---input-border` |\n| Variant     | `--`      | `--negative`      |\n\n**Common Tokens:**\n```css\n/* Input backgrounds */\nvar(--_color-tokens---input-bg--enabled)\nvar(--_color-tokens---input-bg--negative)\n\n/* Input borders */\nvar(--_color-tokens---input-border--enabled)\nvar(--_color-tokens---input-border--negative)\n\n/* State colors */\nvar(--_color-tokens---state--focused)\nvar(--_color-tokens---state--warning)\nvar(--_color-tokens---state--success)\n```\n\n---\n\n## 4. FORM VALIDATION CLASSES\n\n| Class                 | Purpose             | Applied To          |\n| --------------------- | ------------------- | ------------------- |\n| `.validation-invalid` | Invalid/error state | `[data-form-field]` |\n| `.validation-valid`   | Valid/success state | `[data-form-field]` |\n\n```css\n/* Invalid state */\n[data-form-field].validation-invalid input.input[data-form-input] {\n  border-color: var(--_color-tokens---input-border--negative);\n  background-color: var(--_color-tokens---input-bg--negative);\n}\n\n/* Valid state */\n[data-form-field].validation-valid #input-success {\n  display: flex;\n  opacity: 1;\n}\n```\n\n```javascript\n// Toggle validation states\nfield.classList.remove('validation-invalid');\nfield.classList.add('validation-valid');\n```\n\n---\n\n## 5. REDUCED MOTION (MANDATORY)\n\nAll animations MUST respect `prefers-reduced-motion`:\n\n```css\n/* Default animation */\n.element {\n  transition: transform 0.3s ease-out;\n}\n\n/* Disable for reduced motion preference */\n@media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce) {\n  .element {\n    transition: none;\n  }\n}\n```\n\n```javascript\n// Check preference in JS\nconst PREFERS_REDUCED_MOTION = window.matchMedia(\n  '(prefers-reduced-motion: reduce)'\n).matches;\n\nif (!PREFERS_REDUCED_MOTION) {\n  animate(element, { opacity: [0, 1], y: [20, 0] });\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## 6. FOCUS DETECTION (KEYBOARD VS MOUSE)\n\n| Class             | When Applied     | Purpose            |\n| ----------------- | ---------------- | ------------------ |\n| `.using-keyboard` | User presses Tab | Show focus outline |\n| (no class)        | User clicks      | Hide focus outline |\n\n```css\n/* Show focus outline for keyboard users */\nbody.using-keyboard .input:focus {\n  outline: 4px solid var(--_color-tokens---state--focused);\n  outline-offset: 0;\n}\n\n/* Hide focus outline for mouse users */\nbody:not(.using-keyboard) .input:focus {\n  outline: none;\n}\n```\n\n```javascript\n// Detection (from input_focus_handler.js)\ndocument.addEventListener('keydown', (e) => {\n  if (e.key === 'Tab') {\n    document.body.classList.add('using-keyboard');\n  }\n});\n\ndocument.addEventListener('mousedown', () => {\n  document.body.classList.remove('using-keyboard');\n});\n```\n\n---\n\n## 7. CSS QUICK DECISION MATRIX\n\n| Scenario               | Pattern                              |\n| ---------------------- | ------------------------------------ |\n| Read Webflow token     | `var(--_category---sub--variant)`    |\n| Set validation error   | `.validation-invalid` on field       |\n| Set validation success | `.validation-valid` on field         |\n| Add animation          | Check `prefers-reduced-motion` first |\n| Style keyboard focus   | `body.using-keyboard :focus`         |\n| Hide mouse focus       | `body:not(.using-keyboard) :focus`   |\n\n## RELATED RESOURCES\n\n- [`./style_guide.md`](./style_guide.md) — CSS naming, custom property prefixes, attribute selectors, animation CSS, file organization\n- [`quality_standards/patterns_and_naming_enforcement.md`](quality_standards/patterns_and_naming_enforcement.md) — will-change, GPU props, easing, fluid typography, all 4 CSS enforcement subsections\n- [`../javascript/quick_reference.md`](../javascript/quick_reference.md) — JS snippets and one-liners\n- [`../shared/dev_workflow/overview_nav_and_logging.md`](../shared/dev_workflow/overview_nav_and_logging.md) — cross-language commands, decision matrix, debugging checklist","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":193,"totalLines":193,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/css/quick_reference.md","time":{"start":1783915968602,"end":1783915968608}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0626a5c87cdc17c2016a5465c033208191824e2f81410f70ac"}},"id":"prt_f59ad7846001itL18q6RTJrXtI","sessionID":"ses_0a65ac472ffeDn3G1fX5LbU2k8","messageID":"msg_f59ad3525001cKzYybAHwMW9vD"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1783915968618,"sessionID":"ses_0a65ac472ffeDn3G1fX5LbU2k8","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_pyzWZASFP6b2qmZ3TPPWZPTg","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/css/style_guide.md","offset":1,"limit":200},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/css/style_guide.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: \"Webflow CSS Style Guide\"\n3: description: \"CSS naming (BEM with kebab-case), custom property prefixes (font, vw, component, state, global), attribute-selector case-insensitivity, animation property restrictions, and file organization for the Webflow stack.\"\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"webflow css style guide\"\n6:   - \"bem kebab case naming\"\n7:   - \"css custom property prefixes\"\n8:   - \"css attribute selector flag\"\n9:   - \"css animation properties webflow\"\n10: importance_tier: normal\n11: contextType: implementation\n12: version: 3.5.0.2\n13: ---\n14: \n15: # Webflow CSS Style Guide\n16: \n17: > See [`../shared/cross_language_rules.md`](../shared/cross_language_rules.md) for rules that apply to all languages (file naming, comment WHY-not-WHAT, file-header banner shape, platform-specific comment prefixes). This file covers CSS-specific conventions only.\n18: \n19: ---\n20: \n21: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n22: \n23: ### Purpose\n24: \n25: Defines CSS naming (BEM with kebab-case), custom property prefixes, attribute selector conventions, animation property restrictions, and file organization for the Webflow stack.\n26: \n27: ### When to Use\n28: \n29: - Writing new CSS files for Webflow projects\n30: - Reviewing CSS for naming and animation-property compliance\n31: - Adding custom properties or attribute selectors to Webflow markup\n32: \n33: ### Core Principle\n34: \n35: BEM naming + GPU-only animations + case-insensitive attribute selectors prevent the most common Webflow CSS regressions.\n36: \n37: ---\n38: \n39: ## 2. NAMING (BEM WITH KEBAB-CASE)\n40: \n41: ```css\n42: .hero { }                    /* Block */\n43: .hero--title { }             /* Element (double-dash) */\n44: .hero--overlay { }           /* Element */\n45: .hero-featured { }           /* Modifier (single-dash) */\n46: .btn { }                     /* Block */\n47: .btn--icon { }               /* Element */\n48: .btn-primary { }             /* Modifier */\n49: ```\n50: \n51: **Note:** CSS files use snake_case for filenames per [`../shared/cross_language_rules.md`](../shared/cross_language_rules.md) §2 FILE NAMING — but class names use BEM with kebab-case as shown here.\n52: \n53: ---\n54: \n55: ## 3. CUSTOM PROPERTY NAMING\n56: \n57: Use prefixes to indicate scope and purpose:\n58: \n59: | Prefix          | Scope                 | Example                           |\n60: | --------------- | --------------------- | --------------------------------- |\n61: | `--font-*`      | Typography variables  | `--font-from`, `--font-to`        |\n62: | `--vw-*`        | Viewport calculations | `--vw-from`, `--vw-to`            |\n63: | `--component-*` | Component-specific    | `--hero-padding`, `--card-radius` |\n64: | `--state-*`     | Interactive states    | `--state-hover-opacity`           |\n65: | `--global-*`    | Site-wide values      | `--global-max-width`              |\n66: \n67: **Production example from fluid_responsive.css:**\n68: \n69: ```css\n70: :root {\n71:   --font-from: 18;\n72:   --font-to: 18;\n73:   --vw-from: calc(5120 / 100);\n74:   --vw-to: calc(7680 / 100);\n75:   --coefficient: calc((var(--font-to) - var(--font-from)) / (var(--vw-to) - var(--vw-from)));\n76:   --base: calc((var(--font-from) - var(--vw-from) * var(--coefficient)) / 16);\n77: }\n78: ```\n79: \n80: ---\n81: \n82: ## 4. ATTRIBUTE SELECTORS (CASE-INSENSITIVITY)\n83: \n84: **Always use the case-insensitivity flag `i` for custom data attributes:**\n85: \n86: ```css\n87: /* Correct: Case-insensitive (matches \"Base\", \"base\", \"BASE\") */\n88: [data-render-content=\"base\" i] {\n89:   content-visibility: auto;\n90: }\n91: \n92: /* Incorrect: Case-sensitive (only matches exact \"base\") */\n93: [data-render-content=\"base\"] {\n94:   content-visibility: auto;\n95: }\n96: ```\n97: \n98: **Why this matters:**\n99: - Webflow attribute panel may produce inconsistent casing\n100: - Users may type \"Base\" instead of \"base\"\n101: - Prevents silent CSS selector failures\n102: - Browser support: Chrome 49+, Firefox 47+, Safari 9+, Edge 79+\n103: \n104: ---\n105: \n106: ## 5. ANIMATION CSS\n107: \n108: ### GPU-Accelerated Properties Only\n109: \n110: ```css\n111: .animated-element {\n112:   /* GPU-accelerated - USE THESE */\n113:   transform: translateY(0);\n114:   opacity: 1;\n115:   scale: 1;\n116: \n117:   /* Layout properties - AVOID ANIMATING */\n118:   /* width, height, top, left, padding, margin */\n119: }\n120: ```\n121: \n122: ### will-change Management\n123: \n124: ```css\n125: /* Set via JavaScript BEFORE animation starts */\n126: .animating {\n127:   will-change: transform, opacity;\n128: }\n129: \n130: /* Reset after animation completes (via JavaScript) */\n131: .animation-complete {\n132:   will-change: auto;\n133: }\n134: ```\n135: \n136: > **Note:** The dynamic-set pattern (setting `will-change` via JavaScript before animation, resetting after) is detailed in [`quality_standards/patterns_and_naming_enforcement.md`](quality_standards/patterns_and_naming_enforcement.md).\n137: \n138: ### Easing Standards (Aligned with Motion.dev)\n139: \n140: ```css\n141: /* General purpose - smooth deceleration */\n142: transition: transform 0.3s cubic-bezier(0.22, 1, 0.36, 1);\n143: \n144: /* Dramatic entrances - strong deceleration */\n145: transition: opacity 0.6s cubic-bezier(0.16, 1, 0.3, 1);\n146: ```\n147: \n148: ---\n149: \n150: ## 6. FILE ORGANIZATION\n151: \n152: **One file per component type, grouped by category:**\n153: \n154: ```\n155: src/1_css/\n156: ├── animations/          # Reusable animation classes\n157: ├── button/              # Button variants (btn_primary.css, btn_secondary.css)\n158: ├── card/                # Card layouts\n159: ├── form/                # Form elements\n160: ├── global/              # Site-wide styles (fluid_responsive.css, reset.css)\n161: ├── label/               # Label styles\n162: ├── link/                # Link styles\n163: ├── menu/                # Navigation menus\n164: ├── slider/              # Carousel/slider styles\n165: ├── text/                # Typography components\n166: └── video/               # Video player styles\n167: ```\n168: \n169: **Naming conventions:**\n170: - Files: `component_variant.css` (snake_case)\n171: - Classes: `.component--element` (BEM with double-dash for elements)\n172: - Modifiers: `.component-modifier` (single-dash for modifiers)\n173: \n174: ---\n175: \n176: ## 7. COMMENTS & SECTION HEADERS (CSS-SPECIFIC)\n177: \n178: > Cross-language commenting principles (WHY-not-WHAT, no commented-out code, platform prefixes) live in [`../shared/cross_language_rules.md`](../shared/cross_language_rules.md). This section covers CSS-specific comment LAYOUT, FREQUENCY, and CONTENT patterns observed in production.\n179: \n180: ### File Header Banner\n181: \n182: Every CSS file opens with a 3-line banner using `/* */` multi-line comment:\n183: \n184: ```css\n185: /* ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n186:    VIDEO (HLS) - BACKGROUND PLAYER\n187: ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── */\n188: ```\n189: \n190: **Specifications** (matches `anobel.com/src/1_css/video/video_hls_background.css`):\n191: - Opening line: `/* ─` followed by 63 `─` characters\n192: - Title line: 3-space indent, ALL CAPS, may include parentheses for sub-categorization (e.g. `VIDEO (HLS) - BACKGROUND PLAYER`, `FORM: STYLING`), uses ` - ` or `:` as the category-name separator\n193: - Closing line: 63 `─` characters followed by **a space, then `*/`** (`─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── */`)\n194: \n195: **Key difference from JS section headers:** CSS file headers have a SPACE before `*/`. JS section headers glue `*/` to the dashes (`────*/`). Both formats are correct for their respective contexts.\n196: \n197: ### Section Headers (Numbered)\n198: \n199: Within a CSS file, group rules into numbered sections with the same banner shape as the file header:\n200: \n\n(Showing lines 1-200 of 308. Use offset=201 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: \"Webflow CSS Style Guide\"\ndescription: \"CSS naming (BEM with kebab-case), custom property prefixes (font, vw, component, state, global), attribute-selector case-insensitivity, animation property restrictions, and file organization for the Webflow stack.\"\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"webflow css style guide\"\n  - \"bem kebab case naming\"\n  - \"css custom property prefixes\"\n  - \"css attribute selector flag\"\n  - \"css animation properties webflow\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 3.5.0.2\n---\n\n# Webflow CSS Style Guide\n\n> See [`../shared/cross_language_rules.md`](../shared/cross_language_rules.md) for rules that apply to all languages (file naming, comment WHY-not-WHAT, file-header banner shape, platform-specific comment prefixes). This file covers CSS-specific conventions only.\n\n---\n","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/css/style_guide.md","text":"---\ntitle: \"Webflow CSS Style Guide\"\ndescription: \"CSS naming (BEM with kebab-case), custom property prefixes (font, vw, component, state, global), attribute-selector case-insensitivity, animation property restrictions, and file organization for the Webflow stack.\"\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"webflow css style guide\"\n  - \"bem kebab case naming\"\n  - \"css custom property prefixes\"\n  - \"css attribute selector flag\"\n  - \"css animation properties webflow\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 3.5.0.2\n---\n\n# Webflow CSS Style Guide\n\n> See [`../shared/cross_language_rules.md`](../shared/cross_language_rules.md) for rules that apply to all languages (file naming, comment WHY-not-WHAT, file-header banner shape, platform-specific comment prefixes). This file covers CSS-specific conventions only.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Purpose\n\nDefines CSS naming (BEM with kebab-case), custom property prefixes, attribute selector conventions, animation property restrictions, and file organization for the Webflow stack.\n\n### When to Use\n\n- Writing new CSS files for Webflow projects\n- Reviewing CSS for naming and animation-property compliance\n- Adding custom properties or attribute selectors to Webflow markup\n\n### Core Principle\n\nBEM naming + GPU-only animations + case-insensitive attribute selectors prevent the most common Webflow CSS regressions.\n\n---\n\n## 2. NAMING (BEM WITH KEBAB-CASE)\n\n```css\n.hero { }                    /* Block */\n.hero--title { }             /* Element (double-dash) */\n.hero--overlay { }           /* Element */\n.hero-featured { }           /* Modifier (single-dash) */\n.btn { }                     /* Block */\n.btn--icon { }               /* Element */\n.btn-primary { }             /* Modifier */\n```\n\n**Note:** CSS files use snake_case for filenames per [`../shared/cross_language_rules.md`](../shared/cross_language_rules.md) §2 FILE NAMING — but class names use BEM with kebab-case as shown here.\n\n---\n\n## 3. CUSTOM PROPERTY NAMING\n\nUse prefixes to indicate scope and purpose:\n\n| Prefix          | Scope                 | Example                           |\n| --------------- | --------------------- | --------------------------------- |\n| `--font-*`      | Typography variables  | `--font-from`, `--font-to`        |\n| `--vw-*`        | Viewport calculations | `--vw-from`, `--vw-to`            |\n| `--component-*` | Component-specific    | `--hero-padding`, `--card-radius` |\n| `--state-*`     | Interactive states    | `--state-hover-opacity`           |\n| `--global-*`    | Site-wide values      | `--global-max-width`              |\n\n**Production example from fluid_responsive.css:**\n\n```css\n:root {\n  --font-from: 18;\n  --font-to: 18;\n  --vw-from: calc(5120 / 100);\n  --vw-to: calc(7680 / 100);\n  --coefficient: calc((var(--font-to) - var(--font-from)) / (var(--vw-to) - var(--vw-from)));\n  --base: calc((var(--font-from) - var(--vw-from) * var(--coefficient)) / 16);\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## 4. ATTRIBUTE SELECTORS (CASE-INSENSITIVITY)\n\n**Always use the case-insensitivity flag `i` for custom data attributes:**\n\n```css\n/* Correct: Case-insensitive (matches \"Base\", \"base\", \"BASE\") */\n[data-render-content=\"base\" i] {\n  content-visibility: auto;\n}\n\n/* Incorrect: Case-sensitive (only matches exact \"base\") */\n[data-render-content=\"base\"] {\n  content-visibility: auto;\n}\n```\n\n**Why this matters:**\n- Webflow attribute panel may produce inconsistent casing\n- Users may type \"Base\" instead of \"base\"\n- Prevents silent CSS selector failures\n- Browser support: Chrome 49+, Firefox 47+, Safari 9+, Edge 79+\n\n---\n\n## 5. ANIMATION CSS\n\n### GPU-Accelerated Properties Only\n\n```css\n.animated-element {\n  /* GPU-accelerated - USE THESE */\n  transform: translateY(0);\n  opacity: 1;\n  scale: 1;\n\n  /* Layout properties - AVOID ANIMATING */\n  /* width, height, top, left, padding, margin */\n}\n```\n\n### will-change Management\n\n```css\n/* Set via JavaScript BEFORE animation starts */\n.animating {\n  will-change: transform, opacity;\n}\n\n/* Reset after animation completes (via JavaScript) */\n.animation-complete {\n  will-change: auto;\n}\n```\n\n> **Note:** The dynamic-set pattern (setting `will-change` via JavaScript before animation, resetting after) is detailed in [`quality_standards/patterns_and_naming_enforcement.md`](quality_standards/patterns_and_naming_enforcement.md).\n\n### Easing Standards (Aligned with Motion.dev)\n\n```css\n/* General purpose - smooth deceleration */\ntransition: transform 0.3s cubic-bezier(0.22, 1, 0.36, 1);\n\n/* Dramatic entrances - strong deceleration */\ntransition: opacity 0.6s cubic-bezier(0.16, 1, 0.3, 1);\n```\n\n---\n\n## 6. FILE ORGANIZATION\n\n**One file per component type, grouped by category:**\n\n```\nsrc/1_css/\n├── animations/          # Reusable animation classes\n├── button/              # Button variants (btn_primary.css, btn_secondary.css)\n├── card/                # Card layouts\n├── form/                # Form elements\n├── global/              # Site-wide styles (fluid_responsive.css, reset.css)\n├── label/               # Label styles\n├── link/                # Link styles\n├── menu/                # Navigation menus\n├── slider/              # Carousel/slider styles\n├── text/                # Typography components\n└── video/               # Video player styles\n```\n\n**Naming conventions:**\n- Files: `component_variant.css` (snake_case)\n- Classes: `.component--element` (BEM with double-dash for elements)\n- Modifiers: `.component-modifier` (single-dash for modifiers)\n\n---\n\n## 7. COMMENTS & SECTION HEADERS (CSS-SPECIFIC)\n\n> Cross-language commenting principles (WHY-not-WHAT, no commented-out code, platform prefixes) live in [`../shared/cross_language_rules.md`](../shared/cross_language_rules.md). This section covers CSS-specific comment LAYOUT, FREQUENCY, and CONTENT patterns observed in production.\n\n### File Header Banner\n\nEvery CSS file opens with a 3-line banner using `/* */` multi-line comment:\n\n```css\n/* ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n   VIDEO (HLS) - BACKGROUND PLAYER\n─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── */\n```\n\n**Specifications** (matches `anobel.com/src/1_css/video/video_hls_background.css`):\n- Opening line: `/* ─` followed by 63 `─` characters\n- Title line: 3-space indent, ALL CAPS, may include parentheses for sub-categorization (e.g. `VIDEO (HLS) - BACKGROUND PLAYER`, `FORM: STYLING`), uses ` - ` or `:` as the category-name separator\n- Closing line: 63 `─` characters followed by **a space, then `*/`** (`─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── */`)\n\n**Key difference from JS section headers:** CSS file headers have a SPACE before `*/`. JS section headers glue `*/` to the dashes (`────*/`). Both formats are correct for their respective contexts.\n\n### Section Headers (Numbered)\n\nWithin a CSS file, group rules into numbered sections with the same banner shape as the file header:\n","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":200,"totalLines":308,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/css/style_guide.md","time":{"start":1783915968613,"end":1783915968616}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0626a5c87cdc17c2016a5465c0332481919702ab9614e027bf"}},"id":"prt_f59ad785c001LbfI9lVPfYZPQ2","sessionID":"ses_0a65ac472ffeDn3G1fX5LbU2k8","messageID":"msg_f59ad3525001cKzYybAHwMW9vD"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1783915968633,"sessionID":"ses_0a65ac472ffeDn3G1fX5LbU2k8","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_sBEcZWf0VJJkoYMlYWmETzow","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/html/quality_standards.md","offset":1,"limit":200},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/html/quality_standards.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: \"Webflow HTML Quality Standards\"\n3: description: \"HTML quality + enforcement for Webflow projects: data-attribute hygiene, ARIA state-sync validation, custom embed cleanup rules, head/footer custom code panel structure validation.\"\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"webflow html quality standards\"\n6:   - \"data attribute hygiene\"\n7:   - \"aria state sync\"\n8:   - \"custom embed validation\"\n9:   - \"head footer panel structure\"\n10: importance_tier: normal\n11: contextType: implementation\n12: version: 3.5.0.2\n13: ---\n14: \n15: # Webflow HTML Quality Standards\n16: \n17: HTML quality and enforcement rules for the small set of conventions that actually apply in Webflow projects.\n18: \n19: ---\n20: \n21: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n22: \n23: ### Purpose\n24: \n25: Defensive HTML patterns + enforcement rules for Webflow custom embeds, data-attribute hooks, ARIA state synchronization, and head/footer custom code panel structure. Most HTML in Webflow is owned by the Webflow Designer; this file enforces the small contract surface where custom HTML actually lives.\n26: \n27: ### When to Use\n28: \n29: - Adding `data-*` attributes to Webflow Designer markup (custom JS hooks)\n30: - Writing custom embed blocks (Embed element on a page)\n31: - Authoring head/footer custom code panel content (Site Settings or Page Settings)\n32: - Reviewing custom HTML for ARIA state-sync correctness\n33: - Validating that Webflow Designer markup hasn't drifted from JS expectations\n34: \n35: ### Core Principle\n36: \n37: The only HTML you author is the contract surface — `data-*` hooks, ARIA state, custom embed scaffolding, head/footer panel structure. Enforce it strictly so the JS↔markup contract never silently breaks.\n38: \n39: ---\n40: \n41: ## 2. DATA-ATTRIBUTE HYGIENE\n42: \n43: ### Validation Prompt\n44: \n45: > **Check:** Are all `data-*` attributes lowercase-kebab-case? Do component roots have `data-component`? Do triggers have `data-action`? Are bridge attributes (`data-select=\"*\"`, `data-form-field`) shaped correctly?\n46: \n47: ### Pattern Recognition\n48: \n49: **Compliant naming:**\n50: \n51: ```html\n52: <!-- Lowercase, kebab-case, hyphen-separated -->\n53: <div data-component=\"hero\">\n54: <button data-action=\"toggle\" data-target=\"panel-1\">\n55: <div data-form-field>\n56: <input data-form-input type=\"email\">\n57: <div data-select=\"wrapper\">\n58:   <div data-select=\"trigger\">\n59:   <div data-select=\"dropdown\">\n60:     <div data-select=\"option\" data-value=\"opt-1\">\n61: ```\n62: \n63: **Violation patterns:**\n64: \n65: | Violation | Example | Why broken |\n66: |---|---|---|\n67: | camelCase attribute name | `data-formField` | HTML attribute names are case-insensitive — JS dataset coerces to camelCase, but selectors `[data-formField]` fail in CSS (case-sensitive without `i` flag) |\n68: | PascalCase value | `data-component=\"Hero\"` | Inconsistent with snake_case JS naming + CSS attribute selectors fail without `i` flag |\n69: | snake_case attribute name | `data-form_field` | Breaks the `element.dataset.formField` JS access pattern |\n70: | Spaces in value | `data-action=\"open modal\"` | HTML allows it, but breaks `[data-action=\"open modal\"]` selector readability and JS routing |\n71: | Missing component root | trigger but no `data-component` parent | JS event delegation can't scope to a single component instance |\n72: \n73: ### Remediation\n74: \n75: | From | To |\n76: |---|---|\n77: | `data-FormField` | `data-form-field` |\n78: | `data-action=\"OpenModal\"` | `data-action=\"open-modal\"` |\n79: | `data-component=\"HeroSection\"` | `data-component=\"hero-section\"` or `data-component=\"hero\"` |\n80: | `data-form_field` | `data-form-field` |\n81: \n82: Run a repo-wide grep for non-compliant patterns before completion:\n83: \n84: ```bash\n85: # camelCase data attributes\n86: grep -rE 'data-[a-z]+[A-Z]' src/\n87: \n88: # PascalCase values\n89: grep -rE 'data-[a-z-]+=\"[A-Z][^\"]*\"' src/\n90: ```\n91: \n92: ---\n93: \n94: ## 3. EMPTY-VALUE ATTRIBUTE CLEANUP\n95: \n96: ### Validation Prompt\n97: \n98: > **Check:** Are empty value-based attributes (`id=\"\"`, `data-type=\"\"`, `class=\"\"`) removed? Are boolean marker attributes left intact?\n99: \n100: ### Pattern Recognition\n101: \n102: **Compliant: empty value-based attributes removed**\n103: \n104: ```html\n105: <!-- BEFORE: Webflow may emit empty attributes -->\n106: <div id=\"\" class=\"\" data-type=\"\">\n107:   <input type=\"text\" id=\"\" name=\"email\">\n108: </div>\n109: \n110: <!-- AFTER: empty value-based attributes deleted -->\n111: <div>\n112:   <input type=\"text\" name=\"email\">\n113: </div>\n114: ```\n115: \n116: **Compliant: boolean marker attributes preserved**\n117: \n118: ```html\n119: <!-- These attributes have NO value because their PRESENCE is the signal -->\n120: <button disabled>\n121: <details open>\n122: <input type=\"text\" required>\n123: <input type=\"text\" autofocus>\n124: <div data-active>          <!-- Boolean flag — keep even though \"value\" is empty -->\n125: <script async>\n126: <script defer>\n127: ```\n128: \n129: ### Remediation\n130: \n131: `attribute_cleanup.min.js` (production utility script in anobel.com) does this on page load. For static cleanup, the regex pattern:\n132: \n133: | Attribute | Disposition | Rationale |\n134: |---|---|---|\n135: | Empty `id=\"\"` | **Remove** | Invalid HTML, breaks `getElementById()`, causes selector bugs |\n136: | Empty `class=\"\"` | **Remove** | DOM bloat, no functional purpose |\n137: | Empty `data-type=\"\"` (or any value-based data-*) | **Remove** | DOM bloat |\n138: | `data-active` (no value) | **Keep** | Boolean flag — JS reads `element.hasAttribute('data-active')` |\n139: | `disabled` / `required` / `autofocus` | **Keep** | Native boolean attributes |\n140: \n141: ### Common pitfall\n142: \n143: Don't blindly strip every empty attribute. `disabled`, `required`, `autofocus`, `async`, `defer`, `open`, and any `data-*` flag used as a boolean marker MUST be preserved. The discriminator: does JS read this with `hasAttribute()` (keep) or `getAttribute()` (strip if empty)?\n144: \n145: ---\n146: \n147: ## 4. ARIA STATE SYNC ENFORCEMENT\n148: \n149: ### Validation Prompt\n150: \n151: > **Check:** When custom JS toggles a UI state (open/closed, expanded/collapsed, valid/invalid, loading/ready), does it ALSO update the matching ARIA attribute? Are initial ARIA values correct for the initial DOM state?\n152: \n153: ### Pattern Recognition\n154: \n155: **Compliant: ARIA state mirrors DOM state**\n156: \n157: ```html\n158: <!-- Initial state: collapsed -->\n159: <button\n160:   data-component=\"accordion-trigger\"\n161:   aria-expanded=\"false\"\n162:   aria-controls=\"accordion-panel-1\"\n163: >\n164:   Section title\n165: </button>\n166: <div id=\"accordion-panel-1\" role=\"region\" hidden>\n167:   Panel content\n168: </div>\n169: ```\n170: \n171: ```javascript\n172: // JS toggles BOTH the visual state AND the ARIA state\n173: function toggle_accordion(trigger) {\n174:   const panel_id = trigger.getAttribute('aria-controls');\n175:   const panel = document.getElementById(panel_id);\n176:   const is_expanded = trigger.getAttribute('aria-expanded') === 'true';\n177: \n178:   trigger.setAttribute('aria-expanded', is_expanded ? 'false' : 'true');\n179:   panel.toggleAttribute('hidden', is_expanded);\n180: }\n181: ```\n182: \n183: **Non-compliant patterns:**\n184: \n185: | Violation | Example | Fix |\n186: |---|---|---|\n187: | Initial ARIA mismatch | `aria-expanded=\"false\"` on a panel that's visible at page load | Set initial value to match initial visual state |\n188: | State changes without ARIA update | JS adds `.is-open` class but doesn't flip `aria-expanded` | Always pair class toggle with ARIA toggle |\n189: | Wrong ARIA attribute for the role | `aria-pressed` on a non-toggle button | Match ARIA attribute to the widget pattern (button → aria-pressed for toggles, aria-expanded for disclosures) |\n190: | `hidden` attribute desync | Panel visible (`display: block`) but `hidden` attribute still present | When JS shows the panel, remove `hidden`; when hiding, add `hidden` |\n191: \n192: ### Remediation\n193: \n194: For every JS function that changes UI state, audit the corresponding ARIA contract:\n195: \n196: | UI pattern | Required ARIA |\n197: |---|---|\n198: | Disclosure (button + panel) | `aria-expanded` on button, `aria-controls` linking to panel id, `hidden` attribute on panel synced to expanded state |\n199: | Toggle button | `aria-pressed=\"true|false\"` |\n200: | Tab + tabpanel | `aria-selected` on tab, `aria-controls` + `aria-labelledby` linking, `tabindex=\"-1\"` on inactive tabs |\n\n(Showing lines 1-200 of 356. Use offset=201 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: \"Webflow HTML Quality Standards\"\ndescription: \"HTML quality + enforcement for Webflow projects: data-attribute hygiene, ARIA state-sync validation, custom embed cleanup rules, head/footer custom code panel structure validation.\"\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"webflow html quality standards\"\n  - \"data attribute hygiene\"\n  - \"aria state sync\"\n  - \"custom embed validation\"\n  - \"head footer panel structure\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 3.5.0.2\n---\n\n# Webflow HTML Quality Standards\n\nHTML quality and enforcement rules for the small set of conventions that actually apply in Webflow projects.\n\n---\n","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/html/quality_standards.md","text":"---\ntitle: \"Webflow HTML Quality Standards\"\ndescription: \"HTML quality + enforcement for Webflow projects: data-attribute hygiene, ARIA state-sync validation, custom embed cleanup rules, head/footer custom code panel structure validation.\"\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"webflow html quality standards\"\n  - \"data attribute hygiene\"\n  - \"aria state sync\"\n  - \"custom embed validation\"\n  - \"head footer panel structure\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 3.5.0.2\n---\n\n# Webflow HTML Quality Standards\n\nHTML quality and enforcement rules for the small set of conventions that actually apply in Webflow projects.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Purpose\n\nDefensive HTML patterns + enforcement rules for Webflow custom embeds, data-attribute hooks, ARIA state synchronization, and head/footer custom code panel structure. Most HTML in Webflow is owned by the Webflow Designer; this file enforces the small contract surface where custom HTML actually lives.\n\n### When to Use\n\n- Adding `data-*` attributes to Webflow Designer markup (custom JS hooks)\n- Writing custom embed blocks (Embed element on a page)\n- Authoring head/footer custom code panel content (Site Settings or Page Settings)\n- Reviewing custom HTML for ARIA state-sync correctness\n- Validating that Webflow Designer markup hasn't drifted from JS expectations\n\n### Core Principle\n\nThe only HTML you author is the contract surface — `data-*` hooks, ARIA state, custom embed scaffolding, head/footer panel structure. Enforce it strictly so the JS↔markup contract never silently breaks.\n\n---\n\n## 2. DATA-ATTRIBUTE HYGIENE\n\n### Validation Prompt\n\n> **Check:** Are all `data-*` attributes lowercase-kebab-case? Do component roots have `data-component`? Do triggers have `data-action`? Are bridge attributes (`data-select=\"*\"`, `data-form-field`) shaped correctly?\n\n### Pattern Recognition\n\n**Compliant naming:**\n\n```html\n<!-- Lowercase, kebab-case, hyphen-separated -->\n<div data-component=\"hero\">\n<button data-action=\"toggle\" data-target=\"panel-1\">\n<div data-form-field>\n<input data-form-input type=\"email\">\n<div data-select=\"wrapper\">\n  <div data-select=\"trigger\">\n  <div data-select=\"dropdown\">\n    <div data-select=\"option\" data-value=\"opt-1\">\n```\n\n**Violation patterns:**\n\n| Violation | Example | Why broken |\n|---|---|---|\n| camelCase attribute name | `data-formField` | HTML attribute names are case-insensitive — JS dataset coerces to camelCase, but selectors `[data-formField]` fail in CSS (case-sensitive without `i` flag) |\n| PascalCase value | `data-component=\"Hero\"` | Inconsistent with snake_case JS naming + CSS attribute selectors fail without `i` flag |\n| snake_case attribute name | `data-form_field` | Breaks the `element.dataset.formField` JS access pattern |\n| Spaces in value | `data-action=\"open modal\"` | HTML allows it, but breaks `[data-action=\"open modal\"]` selector readability and JS routing |\n| Missing component root | trigger but no `data-component` parent | JS event delegation can't scope to a single component instance |\n\n### Remediation\n\n| From | To |\n|---|---|\n| `data-FormField` | `data-form-field` |\n| `data-action=\"OpenModal\"` | `data-action=\"open-modal\"` |\n| `data-component=\"HeroSection\"` | `data-component=\"hero-section\"` or `data-component=\"hero\"` |\n| `data-form_field` | `data-form-field` |\n\nRun a repo-wide grep for non-compliant patterns before completion:\n\n```bash\n# camelCase data attributes\ngrep -rE 'data-[a-z]+[A-Z]' src/\n\n# PascalCase values\ngrep -rE 'data-[a-z-]+=\"[A-Z][^\"]*\"' src/\n```\n\n---\n\n## 3. EMPTY-VALUE ATTRIBUTE CLEANUP\n\n### Validation Prompt\n\n> **Check:** Are empty value-based attributes (`id=\"\"`, `data-type=\"\"`, `class=\"\"`) removed? Are boolean marker attributes left intact?\n\n### Pattern Recognition\n\n**Compliant: empty value-based attributes removed**\n\n```html\n<!-- BEFORE: Webflow may emit empty attributes -->\n<div id=\"\" class=\"\" data-type=\"\">\n  <input type=\"text\" id=\"\" name=\"email\">\n</div>\n\n<!-- AFTER: empty value-based attributes deleted -->\n<div>\n  <input type=\"text\" name=\"email\">\n</div>\n```\n\n**Compliant: boolean marker attributes preserved**\n\n```html\n<!-- These attributes have NO value because their PRESENCE is the signal -->\n<button disabled>\n<details open>\n<input type=\"text\" required>\n<input type=\"text\" autofocus>\n<div data-active>          <!-- Boolean flag — keep even though \"value\" is empty -->\n<script async>\n<script defer>\n```\n\n### Remediation\n\n`attribute_cleanup.min.js` (production utility script in anobel.com) does this on page load. For static cleanup, the regex pattern:\n\n| Attribute | Disposition | Rationale |\n|---|---|---|\n| Empty `id=\"\"` | **Remove** | Invalid HTML, breaks `getElementById()`, causes selector bugs |\n| Empty `class=\"\"` | **Remove** | DOM bloat, no functional purpose |\n| Empty `data-type=\"\"` (or any value-based data-*) | **Remove** | DOM bloat |\n| `data-active` (no value) | **Keep** | Boolean flag — JS reads `element.hasAttribute('data-active')` |\n| `disabled` / `required` / `autofocus` | **Keep** | Native boolean attributes |\n\n### Common pitfall\n\nDon't blindly strip every empty attribute. `disabled`, `required`, `autofocus`, `async`, `defer`, `open`, and any `data-*` flag used as a boolean marker MUST be preserved. The discriminator: does JS read this with `hasAttribute()` (keep) or `getAttribute()` (strip if empty)?\n\n---\n\n## 4. ARIA STATE SYNC ENFORCEMENT\n\n### Validation Prompt\n\n> **Check:** When custom JS toggles a UI state (open/closed, expanded/collapsed, valid/invalid, loading/ready), does it ALSO update the matching ARIA attribute? Are initial ARIA values correct for the initial DOM state?\n\n### Pattern Recognition\n\n**Compliant: ARIA state mirrors DOM state**\n\n```html\n<!-- Initial state: collapsed -->\n<button\n  data-component=\"accordion-trigger\"\n  aria-expanded=\"false\"\n  aria-controls=\"accordion-panel-1\"\n>\n  Section title\n</button>\n<div id=\"accordion-panel-1\" role=\"region\" hidden>\n  Panel content\n</div>\n```\n\n```javascript\n// JS toggles BOTH the visual state AND the ARIA state\nfunction toggle_accordion(trigger) {\n  const panel_id = trigger.getAttribute('aria-controls');\n  const panel = document.getElementById(panel_id);\n  const is_expanded = trigger.getAttribute('aria-expanded') === 'true';\n\n  trigger.setAttribute('aria-expanded', is_expanded ? 'false' : 'true');\n  panel.toggleAttribute('hidden', is_expanded);\n}\n```\n\n**Non-compliant patterns:**\n\n| Violation | Example | Fix |\n|---|---|---|\n| Initial ARIA mismatch | `aria-expanded=\"false\"` on a panel that's visible at page load | Set initial value to match initial visual state |\n| State changes without ARIA update | JS adds `.is-open` class but doesn't flip `aria-expanded` | Always pair class toggle with ARIA toggle |\n| Wrong ARIA attribute for the role | `aria-pressed` on a non-toggle button | Match ARIA attribute to the widget pattern (button → aria-pressed for toggles, aria-expanded for disclosures) |\n| `hidden` attribute desync | Panel visible (`display: block`) but `hidden` attribute still present | When JS shows the panel, remove `hidden`; when hiding, add `hidden` |\n\n### Remediation\n\nFor every JS function that changes UI state, audit the corresponding ARIA contract:\n\n| UI pattern | Required ARIA |\n|---|---|\n| Disclosure (button + panel) | `aria-expanded` on button, `aria-controls` linking to panel id, `hidden` attribute on panel synced to expanded state |\n| Toggle button | `aria-pressed=\"true|false\"` |\n| Tab + tabpanel | `aria-selected` on tab, `aria-controls` + `aria-labelledby` linking, `tabindex=\"-1\"` on inactive tabs |","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":200,"totalLines":356,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/html/quality_standards.md","time":{"start":1783915968619,"end":1783915968630}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0626a5c87cdc17c2016a5465c0332c819192e5c42be1c6ef1b"}},"id":"prt_f59ad7867001vnWMuUnYYxOhQw","sessionID":"ses_0a65ac472ffeDn3G1fX5LbU2k8","messageID":"msg_f59ad3525001cKzYybAHwMW9vD"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1783915968633,"sessionID":"ses_0a65ac472ffeDn3G1fX5LbU2k8","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_WJEibD1g2rHf6bzJT76VNPbO","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/html/style_guide.md","offset":1,"limit":200},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/html/style_guide.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: \"Webflow HTML Style Guide\"\n3: description: \"Data-attribute naming conventions, semantic HTML preferences, and ARIA basics for Webflow projects. Most HTML in Webflow projects is managed by the Webflow Designer; this file covers the conventions that apply to custom embeds, data attributes used by JS, and accessibility patterns.\"\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"webflow html style guide\"\n6:   - \"webflow data attribute naming\"\n7:   - \"webflow custom embed conventions\"\n8:   - \"webflow aria basics\"\n9: importance_tier: normal\n10: contextType: implementation\n11: version: 3.5.0.2\n12: ---\n13: \n14: # Webflow HTML Style Guide\n15: \n16: > See [`../shared/cross_language_rules.md`](../shared/cross_language_rules.md) for rules that apply to all languages.\n17: \n18: ---\n19: \n20: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n21: \n22: ### Purpose\n23: \n24: Documents the small set of HTML conventions that DO apply to Webflow projects (data-attribute naming, semantic HTML for custom embeds, ARIA basics) and points at Webflow Designer documentation for everything else.\n25: \n26: ### When to Use\n27: \n28: - Adding data-attribute hooks for custom JavaScript\n29: - Writing custom embed HTML inside Webflow\n30: - Syncing ARIA state from JavaScript-driven interactions\n31: - Deciding whether a markup question belongs to Webflow Designer or to custom code\n32: \n33: ### Core Principle\n34: \n35: Most HTML in Webflow is owned by the Webflow Designer; custom HTML conventions only cover the contract surface (data attributes + ARIA).\n36: \n37: ---\n38: \n39: ## 2. SCOPE\n40: \n41: In Webflow projects, **most HTML is managed by the Webflow Designer**. Site authors don't hand-write markup for layout, components, or content blocks — those are designed visually and exported by Webflow's CDN delivery. This style guide covers the small but important set of HTML conventions that DO apply when writing custom code:\n42: \n43: 1. Data-attribute naming for JS-targetable hooks\n44: 2. Semantic HTML for custom embed blocks\n45: 3. ARIA basics for keyboard accessibility\n46: 4. Comment style for **page Head + Footer custom code panels** (§7) — sections, inline labels, end-markers, sub-numbering\n47: 5. Where to find Webflow Designer best practices\n48: \n49: ---\n50: \n51: ## 3. DATA-ATTRIBUTE CONVENTIONS\n52: \n53: Data attributes are the contract between Webflow Designer markup and the custom JavaScript that targets it. Use kebab-case for all attribute names.\n54: \n55: ### Component identifiers\n56: \n57: The `data-component` attribute marks the root of a JS-managed component:\n58: \n59: ```html\n60: <div data-component=\"hero\">…</div>\n61: <div data-component=\"modal\">…</div>\n62: <div data-component=\"accordion\">…</div>\n63: ```\n64: \n65: JS targets these with `[data-component=\"name\"]` selectors.\n66: \n67: ### Action attributes\n68: \n69: The `data-action` attribute declares what a clickable element does. Values mirror the semantic verb prefixes used in JS (`toggle`, `expand`, `collapse`, `remove`):\n70: \n71: ```html\n72: <button data-action=\"toggle\">Toggle panel</button>\n73: <button data-action=\"expand\">Show details</button>\n74: <button data-action=\"collapse\">Hide details</button>\n75: <button data-action=\"remove\">Delete item</button>\n76: ```\n77: \n78: JS routes these via a single delegated event listener that reads `element.dataset.action` and dispatches to the matching handler (see [`../javascript/quality_standards/init_dom_error_and_async.md`](../javascript/quality_standards/init_dom_error_and_async.md) §13 Action Routing Pattern).\n79: \n80: ### Trigger / target patterns\n81: \n82: Use `data-trigger` on the element that initiates an action and `data-target` to reference the element it affects:\n83: \n84: ```html\n85: <!-- data-trigger: the element JS listens on -->\n86: <div data-trigger>…</div>\n87: \n88: <!-- data-target: points to an id that JS resolves -->\n89: <button data-action=\"toggle\" data-target=\"panel-1\">Toggle</button>\n90: <div id=\"panel-1\" hidden>…</div>\n91: ```\n92: \n93: ### Form-field state markers\n94: \n95: Form validation state flows through `data-form-field` containers and `data-form-input` elements:\n96: \n97: ```html\n98: <div data-form-field>\n99:   <input data-form-input class=\"input\" type=\"text\" />\n100: </div>\n101: ```\n102: \n103: Validation JS toggles `.validation-invalid` / `.validation-valid` classes on the `[data-form-field]` container (see [`../javascript/quick_reference.md`](../javascript/quick_reference.md) §10 Form Validation Classes).\n104: \n105: ### Custom select bridge attributes\n106: \n107: When a styled `<div>`-based select must integrate with native form submission or Finsweet list-sort, the bridge pattern uses these attributes:\n108: \n109: ```html\n110: <!-- Before bridge initialization -->\n111: <div data-select=\"wrapper\" fs-list-element=\"sort-trigger\">\n112:   <div data-select=\"trigger\">\n113:     <input data-select=\"input\" placeholder=\"Sort by...\" readonly />\n114:   </div>\n115:   <div data-select=\"dropdown\">\n116:     <div data-select=\"option\" data-value=\"date-asc\">Date (Oldest)</div>\n117:     <div data-select=\"option\" data-value=\"date-desc\">Date (Newest)</div>\n118:   </div>\n119: </div>\n120: ```\n121: \n122: | Attribute                 | Purpose                                                 |\n123: | ------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------- |\n124: | `data-select=\"wrapper\"`   | Container targeted by CustomSelect                      |\n125: | `data-select=\"input\"`     | Displays current selection value                        |\n126: | `data-select=\"option\"`    | Selectable option element                               |\n127: | `data-value`              | The actual value synced to the hidden native `<select>` |\n128: | `data-select-initialized` | State marker set after bridge attaches                  |\n129: \n130: See [`../implementation/webflow_patterns/overview_limits_and_collection_lists.md`](../implementation/webflow_patterns/overview_limits_and_collection_lists.md) §8 for the complete bridge pattern.\n131: \n132: ### Per-item data attributes in collection lists\n133: \n134: Since Webflow duplicates `id` attributes across collection items, use `dataset` properties as stable per-item handles:\n135: \n136: ```html\n137: <!-- After JS initialization, each .w-dyn-item carries stable data-* handles -->\n138: <div class=\"w-dyn-item\" data-item-index=\"0\" data-item-id=\"abc123\" data-item-slug=\"my-post\">\n139:   <span data-field=\"title\">Post Title</span>\n140:   <span data-cms-id>abc123</span>\n141: </div>\n142: ```\n143: \n144: | Attribute            | Source                           | Purpose                          |\n145: | -------------------- | -------------------------------- | -------------------------------- |\n146: | `data-item-index`    | JS-assigned during init          | Stable positional index          |\n147: | `data-item-id`       | Copied from `data-cms-id` text   | CMS item identifier              |\n148: | `data-item-slug`     | Copied from `data-cms-slug` text | URL-friendly identifier          |\n149: | `data-field=\"title\"` | Designer-set (CMS bind)          | Field-binding handle             |\n150: | `data-cms-id`        | Designer-set (CMS bind)          | Raw CMS item ID                  |\n151: | `data-initialized`   | JS-assigned after first init     | Guards against re-initialization |\n152: \n153: ### DOM attribute hygiene\n154: \n155: Remove empty value-based attributes to keep markup clean. Never remove boolean marker attributes:\n156: \n157: | Attribute               | Disposition   | Rationale                        |\n158: | ----------------------- | ------------- | -------------------------------- |\n159: | Empty `id=\"\"`           | Always remove | Invalid HTML, selector bugs      |\n160: | Empty `data-type=\"\"`    | Remove        | DOM bloat, no functional purpose |\n161: | `data-active` (boolean) | Never remove  | Boolean flag used by JS logic    |\n162: \n163: ---\n164: \n165: ## 4. SEMANTIC HTML\n166: \n167: Prefer semantic elements over `<div>` when the element has a meaningful role:\n168: \n169: - `<button>` for clickable actions (not `<div onclick=\"…\">`)\n170: - `<nav>` for navigation regions\n171: - `<main>` for primary page content\n172: - `<article>` for self-contained content blocks\n173: - `<section>` for thematically grouped content\n174: - `<header>` / `<footer>` for page or section framing\n175: \n176: The Webflow Designer's tag-override feature lets you set the underlying HTML tag on any element — use it to promote `<div>` containers to semantic equivalents without losing Designer layout control.\n177: \n178: ---\n179: \n180: ## 5. ARIA BASICS\n181: \n182: When custom JavaScript adds interactive behavior to Webflow markup, sync the ARIA state:\n183: \n184: ```html\n185: <button data-component=\"accordion-trigger\" aria-expanded=\"false\" aria-controls=\"accordion-panel-1\">\n186:   Section title\n187: </button>\n188: <div id=\"accordion-panel-1\" role=\"region\" hidden>…</div>\n189: ```\n190: \n191: When the JS toggles the panel, it must update `aria-expanded` and `hidden` together. The action-routing pattern in [`../javascript/quality_standards/init_dom_error_and_async.md`](../javascript/quality_standards/init_dom_error_and_async.md) §13 handles this — the `expand` and `collapse` actions set `aria-expanded` on the target element.\n192: \n193: ---\n194: \n195: ## 6. WEBFLOW DESIGNER REFERENCE\n196: \n197: For Webflow Designer-level decisions (when to use a Symbol vs a Component, Collection list slots, breakpoints, native interactions vs custom JS), refer to:\n198: \n199: - [Webflow University](https://university.webflow.com)\n200: - [Webflow Designer documentation](https://help.webflow.com)\n\n(Showing lines 1-200 of 399. Use offset=201 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: \"Webflow HTML Style Guide\"\ndescription: \"Data-attribute naming conventions, semantic HTML preferences, and ARIA basics for Webflow projects. Most HTML in Webflow projects is managed by the Webflow Designer; this file covers the conventions that apply to custom embeds, data attributes used by JS, and accessibility patterns.\"\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"webflow html style guide\"\n  - \"webflow data attribute naming\"\n  - \"webflow custom embed conventions\"\n  - \"webflow aria basics\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 3.5.0.2\n---\n\n# Webflow HTML Style Guide\n\n> See [`../shared/cross_language_rules.md`](../shared/cross_language_rules.md) for rules that apply to all languages.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/html/style_guide.md","text":"---\ntitle: \"Webflow HTML Style Guide\"\ndescription: \"Data-attribute naming conventions, semantic HTML preferences, and ARIA basics for Webflow projects. Most HTML in Webflow projects is managed by the Webflow Designer; this file covers the conventions that apply to custom embeds, data attributes used by JS, and accessibility patterns.\"\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"webflow html style guide\"\n  - \"webflow data attribute naming\"\n  - \"webflow custom embed conventions\"\n  - \"webflow aria basics\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 3.5.0.2\n---\n\n# Webflow HTML Style Guide\n\n> See [`../shared/cross_language_rules.md`](../shared/cross_language_rules.md) for rules that apply to all languages.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Purpose\n\nDocuments the small set of HTML conventions that DO apply to Webflow projects (data-attribute naming, semantic HTML for custom embeds, ARIA basics) and points at Webflow Designer documentation for everything else.\n\n### When to Use\n\n- Adding data-attribute hooks for custom JavaScript\n- Writing custom embed HTML inside Webflow\n- Syncing ARIA state from JavaScript-driven interactions\n- Deciding whether a markup question belongs to Webflow Designer or to custom code\n\n### Core Principle\n\nMost HTML in Webflow is owned by the Webflow Designer; custom HTML conventions only cover the contract surface (data attributes + ARIA).\n\n---\n\n## 2. SCOPE\n\nIn Webflow projects, **most HTML is managed by the Webflow Designer**. Site authors don't hand-write markup for layout, components, or content blocks — those are designed visually and exported by Webflow's CDN delivery. This style guide covers the small but important set of HTML conventions that DO apply when writing custom code:\n\n1. Data-attribute naming for JS-targetable hooks\n2. Semantic HTML for custom embed blocks\n3. ARIA basics for keyboard accessibility\n4. Comment style for **page Head + Footer custom code panels** (§7) — sections, inline labels, end-markers, sub-numbering\n5. Where to find Webflow Designer best practices\n\n---\n\n## 3. DATA-ATTRIBUTE CONVENTIONS\n\nData attributes are the contract between Webflow Designer markup and the custom JavaScript that targets it. Use kebab-case for all attribute names.\n\n### Component identifiers\n\nThe `data-component` attribute marks the root of a JS-managed component:\n\n```html\n<div data-component=\"hero\">…</div>\n<div data-component=\"modal\">…</div>\n<div data-component=\"accordion\">…</div>\n```\n\nJS targets these with `[data-component=\"name\"]` selectors.\n\n### Action attributes\n\nThe `data-action` attribute declares what a clickable element does. Values mirror the semantic verb prefixes used in JS (`toggle`, `expand`, `collapse`, `remove`):\n\n```html\n<button data-action=\"toggle\">Toggle panel</button>\n<button data-action=\"expand\">Show details</button>\n<button data-action=\"collapse\">Hide details</button>\n<button data-action=\"remove\">Delete item</button>\n```\n\nJS routes these via a single delegated event listener that reads `element.dataset.action` and dispatches to the matching handler (see [`../javascript/quality_standards/init_dom_error_and_async.md`](../javascript/quality_standards/init_dom_error_and_async.md) §13 Action Routing Pattern).\n\n### Trigger / target patterns\n\nUse `data-trigger` on the element that initiates an action and `data-target` to reference the element it affects:\n\n```html\n<!-- data-trigger: the element JS listens on -->\n<div data-trigger>…</div>\n\n<!-- data-target: points to an id that JS resolves -->\n<button data-action=\"toggle\" data-target=\"panel-1\">Toggle</button>\n<div id=\"panel-1\" hidden>…</div>\n```\n\n### Form-field state markers\n\nForm validation state flows through `data-form-field` containers and `data-form-input` elements:\n\n```html\n<div data-form-field>\n  <input data-form-input class=\"input\" type=\"text\" />\n</div>\n```\n\nValidation JS toggles `.validation-invalid` / `.validation-valid` classes on the `[data-form-field]` container (see [`../javascript/quick_reference.md`](../javascript/quick_reference.md) §10 Form Validation Classes).\n\n### Custom select bridge attributes\n\nWhen a styled `<div>`-based select must integrate with native form submission or Finsweet list-sort, the bridge pattern uses these attributes:\n\n```html\n<!-- Before bridge initialization -->\n<div data-select=\"wrapper\" fs-list-element=\"sort-trigger\">\n  <div data-select=\"trigger\">\n    <input data-select=\"input\" placeholder=\"Sort by...\" readonly />\n  </div>\n  <div data-select=\"dropdown\">\n    <div data-select=\"option\" data-value=\"date-asc\">Date (Oldest)</div>\n    <div data-select=\"option\" data-value=\"date-desc\">Date (Newest)</div>\n  </div>\n</div>\n```\n\n| Attribute                 | Purpose                                                 |\n| ------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------- |\n| `data-select=\"wrapper\"`   | Container targeted by CustomSelect                      |\n| `data-select=\"input\"`     | Displays current selection value                        |\n| `data-select=\"option\"`    | Selectable option element                               |\n| `data-value`              | The actual value synced to the hidden native `<select>` |\n| `data-select-initialized` | State marker set after bridge attaches                  |\n\nSee [`../implementation/webflow_patterns/overview_limits_and_collection_lists.md`](../implementation/webflow_patterns/overview_limits_and_collection_lists.md) §8 for the complete bridge pattern.\n\n### Per-item data attributes in collection lists\n\nSince Webflow duplicates `id` attributes across collection items, use `dataset` properties as stable per-item handles:\n\n```html\n<!-- After JS initialization, each .w-dyn-item carries stable data-* handles -->\n<div class=\"w-dyn-item\" data-item-index=\"0\" data-item-id=\"abc123\" data-item-slug=\"my-post\">\n  <span data-field=\"title\">Post Title</span>\n  <span data-cms-id>abc123</span>\n</div>\n```\n\n| Attribute            | Source                           | Purpose                          |\n| -------------------- | -------------------------------- | -------------------------------- |\n| `data-item-index`    | JS-assigned during init          | Stable positional index          |\n| `data-item-id`       | Copied from `data-cms-id` text   | CMS item identifier              |\n| `data-item-slug`     | Copied from `data-cms-slug` text | URL-friendly identifier          |\n| `data-field=\"title\"` | Designer-set (CMS bind)          | Field-binding handle             |\n| `data-cms-id`        | Designer-set (CMS bind)          | Raw CMS item ID                  |\n| `data-initialized`   | JS-assigned after first init     | Guards against re-initialization |\n\n### DOM attribute hygiene\n\nRemove empty value-based attributes to keep markup clean. Never remove boolean marker attributes:\n\n| Attribute               | Disposition   | Rationale                        |\n| ----------------------- | ------------- | -------------------------------- |\n| Empty `id=\"\"`           | Always remove | Invalid HTML, selector bugs      |\n| Empty `data-type=\"\"`    | Remove        | DOM bloat, no functional purpose |\n| `data-active` (boolean) | Never remove  | Boolean flag used by JS logic    |\n\n---\n\n## 4. SEMANTIC HTML\n\nPrefer semantic elements over `<div>` when the element has a meaningful role:\n\n- `<button>` for clickable actions (not `<div onclick=\"…\">`)\n- `<nav>` for navigation regions\n- `<main>` for primary page content\n- `<article>` for self-contained content blocks\n- `<section>` for thematically grouped content\n- `<header>` / `<footer>` for page or section framing\n\nThe Webflow Designer's tag-override feature lets you set the underlying HTML tag on any element — use it to promote `<div>` containers to semantic equivalents without losing Designer layout control.\n\n---\n\n## 5. ARIA BASICS\n\nWhen custom JavaScript adds interactive behavior to Webflow markup, sync the ARIA state:\n\n```html\n<button data-component=\"accordion-trigger\" aria-expanded=\"false\" aria-controls=\"accordion-panel-1\">\n  Section title\n</button>\n<div id=\"accordion-panel-1\" role=\"region\" hidden>…</div>\n```\n\nWhen the JS toggles the panel, it must update `aria-expanded` and `hidden` together. The action-routing pattern in [`../javascript/quality_standards/init_dom_error_and_async.md`](../javascript/quality_standards/init_dom_error_and_async.md) §13 handles this — the `expand` and `collapse` actions set `aria-expanded` on the target element.\n\n---\n\n## 6. WEBFLOW DESIGNER REFERENCE\n\nFor Webflow Designer-level decisions (when to use a Symbol vs a Component, Collection list slots, breakpoints, native interactions vs custom JS), refer to:\n\n- [Webflow University](https://university.webflow.com)\n- [Webflow Designer documentation](https://help.webflow.com)","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":200,"totalLines":399,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/html/style_guide.md","time":{"start":1783915968621,"end":1783915968632}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0626a5c87cdc17c2016a5465c033308191acd42c1e938f1cbd"}},"id":"prt_f59ad786c001UjjgkRgBWmIY5T","sessionID":"ses_0a65ac472ffeDn3G1fX5LbU2k8","messageID":"msg_f59ad3525001cKzYybAHwMW9vD"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1783915968636,"sessionID":"ses_0a65ac472ffeDn3G1fX5LbU2k8","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_P78HYyfyjwWnHpmVjWVwwFdR","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/implementation/third_party_integrations/overview_hls_and_lenis.md","offset":1,"limit":100},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/implementation/third_party_integrations/overview_hls_and_lenis.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: Third-Party Library Integrations\n3: description: Reference guide for integrating external JavaScript libraries in Webflow projects, with production-tested patterns.\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"webflow third party libraries\"\n6:   - \"hls js video streaming\"\n7:   - \"external library integration\"\n8:   - \"library loading pattern webflow\"\n9: importance_tier: normal\n10: contextType: implementation\n11: version: 3.5.0.4\n12: ---\n13: \n14: # Third-Party Library Integrations\n15: \n16: Reference guide for integrating external JavaScript libraries in Webflow projects, with production-tested patterns following code quality standards.\n17: \n18: ---\n19: \n20: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n21: \n22: ### Purpose\n23: Reference guide for integrating external JavaScript libraries in Webflow projects.\n24: \n25: ### When to Use\n26: - Integrating new third-party libraries\n27: - Managing dependencies (CDN, versions)\n28: - Handling external script loading\n29: \n30: ### Integration Principles\n31: \n32: 1. **CDN-first loading** - Use jsDelivr or unpkg for reliable delivery\n33: 2. **Version pinning** - Always pin to specific versions for stability\n34: 3. **Feature detection** - Check library availability before use\n35: 4. **Graceful fallbacks** - Handle missing/failed libraries gracefully\n36: 5. **Memory management** - Proper cleanup to prevent leaks\n37: \n38: ### Loading Pattern\n39: \n40: ```javascript\n41: const LIBRARY_CDN_URL = 'https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/library@{version}';\n42: \n43: async function load_library() {\n44:   if (typeof window.Library !== 'undefined') {\n45:     return true;\n46:   }\n47: \n48:   return new Promise((resolve) => {\n49:     const script = document.createElement('script');\n50:     script.src = LIBRARY_CDN_URL;\n51:     script.async = true;\n52:     script.onload = () => resolve(true);\n53:     script.onerror = () => resolve(false);\n54:     document.head.appendChild(script);\n55:   });\n56: }\n57: ```\n58: \n59: ---\n60: \n61: ## 2. HLS.JS (VIDEO STREAMING)\n62: \n63: HTTP Live Streaming library for adaptive video playback in non-Safari browsers.\n64: \n65: ### CDN URL\n66: \n67: ```html\n68: <!-- Preload for critical video pages -->\n69: <link rel=\"preload\" href=\"https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/hls.js@{version}\" as=\"script\">\n70: \n71: <!-- Load with defer -->\n72: <script src=\"https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/hls.js@{version}\" defer></script>\n73: ```\n74: \n75: ### Feature Detection\n76: \n77: ```javascript\n78: const test_video = document.createElement('video');\n79: const safari_native = !!test_video.canPlayType('application/vnd.apple.mpegurl');\n80: const can_use_hls_js = !!(window.Hls && Hls.isSupported()) && !safari_native;\n81: ```\n82: \n83: ### Basic Setup\n84: \n85: ```javascript\n86: if (safari_native) {\n87:   video.src = hls_source_url;\n88:   video.addEventListener('loadedmetadata', on_ready, { once: true });\n89: } else if (can_use_hls_js) {\n90:   const hls = new Hls({ maxBufferLength: 8 }); // Low buffer for hover videos\n91:   hls.on(Hls.Events.MEDIA_ATTACHED, () => hls.loadSource(hls_source_url));\n92:   hls.on(Hls.Events.MANIFEST_PARSED, on_ready);\n93:   hls.attachMedia(video);\n94:   player._hls = hls; // Store reference for cleanup\n95: }\n96: ```\n97: \n98: ### Error Handling\n99: \n100: ```javascript\n\n(Showing lines 1-100 of 214. Use offset=101 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: Third-Party Library Integrations\ndescription: Reference guide for integrating external JavaScript libraries in Webflow projects, with production-tested patterns.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"webflow third party libraries\"\n  - \"hls js video streaming\"\n  - \"external library integration\"\n  - \"library loading pattern webflow\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 3.5.0.4\n---\n\n# Third-Party Library Integrations\n\nReference guide for integrating external JavaScript libraries in Webflow projects, with production-tested patterns following code quality standards.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/implementation/third_party_integrations/overview_hls_and_lenis.md","text":"---\ntitle: Third-Party Library Integrations\ndescription: Reference guide for integrating external JavaScript libraries in Webflow projects, with production-tested patterns.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"webflow third party libraries\"\n  - \"hls js video streaming\"\n  - \"external library integration\"\n  - \"library loading pattern webflow\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 3.5.0.4\n---\n\n# Third-Party Library Integrations\n\nReference guide for integrating external JavaScript libraries in Webflow projects, with production-tested patterns following code quality standards.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Purpose\nReference guide for integrating external JavaScript libraries in Webflow projects.\n\n### When to Use\n- Integrating new third-party libraries\n- Managing dependencies (CDN, versions)\n- Handling external script loading\n\n### Integration Principles\n\n1. **CDN-first loading** - Use jsDelivr or unpkg for reliable delivery\n2. **Version pinning** - Always pin to specific versions for stability\n3. **Feature detection** - Check library availability before use\n4. **Graceful fallbacks** - Handle missing/failed libraries gracefully\n5. **Memory management** - Proper cleanup to prevent leaks\n\n### Loading Pattern\n\n```javascript\nconst LIBRARY_CDN_URL = 'https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/library@{version}';\n\nasync function load_library() {\n  if (typeof window.Library !== 'undefined') {\n    return true;\n  }\n\n  return new Promise((resolve) => {\n    const script = document.createElement('script');\n    script.src = LIBRARY_CDN_URL;\n    script.async = true;\n    script.onload = () => resolve(true);\n    script.onerror = () => resolve(false);\n    document.head.appendChild(script);\n  });\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## 2. HLS.JS (VIDEO STREAMING)\n\nHTTP Live Streaming library for adaptive video playback in non-Safari browsers.\n\n### CDN URL\n\n```html\n<!-- Preload for critical video pages -->\n<link rel=\"preload\" href=\"https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/hls.js@{version}\" as=\"script\">\n\n<!-- Load with defer -->\n<script src=\"https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/hls.js@{version}\" defer></script>\n```\n\n### Feature Detection\n\n```javascript\nconst test_video = document.createElement('video');\nconst safari_native = !!test_video.canPlayType('application/vnd.apple.mpegurl');\nconst can_use_hls_js = !!(window.Hls && Hls.isSupported()) && !safari_native;\n```\n\n### Basic Setup\n\n```javascript\nif (safari_native) {\n  video.src = hls_source_url;\n  video.addEventListener('loadedmetadata', on_ready, { once: true });\n} else if (can_use_hls_js) {\n  const hls = new Hls({ maxBufferLength: 8 }); // Low buffer for hover videos\n  hls.on(Hls.Events.MEDIA_ATTACHED, () => hls.loadSource(hls_source_url));\n  hls.on(Hls.Events.MANIFEST_PARSED, on_ready);\n  hls.attachMedia(video);\n  player._hls = hls; // Store reference for cleanup\n}\n```\n\n### Error Handling\n\n```javascript","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":100,"totalLines":214,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/implementation/third_party_integrations/overview_hls_and_lenis.md","time":{"start":1783915968622,"end":1783915968634}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0626a5c87cdc17c2016a5465c033348191a01ebb71e234fdd5"}},"id":"prt_f59ad786d001P3RP5r3kkbIdGp","sessionID":"ses_0a65ac472ffeDn3G1fX5LbU2k8","messageID":"msg_f59ad3525001cKzYybAHwMW9vD"}}
